<HEADLINE> Hasina's Malaysia Trip to Promote Trade, Investment: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina will leave here for Kuala Lumpur Monday morning to hold
talks with Malaysian leader Mahathir Mohammad for enhanced trade
and investment, Foreign Minister Abdus Samad Azad told a press
conference here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister, officially disclosing the Hasina's
itinerary, said the prime minister's visit has diplomatic
significance in the backdrop of Malaysian Ambassador to the United
Nations becoming the chairperson of U.N. Security Council in
August and the imminent millennium summit of the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Increase of Malaysian investment and expansion of bilateral
trade will figure prominently in the official talks between the
prime ministers of the two countries, Azad said, adding that they
would also emphasize on the export of more Bangladeshi labors to
Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia, the third largest investor in Bangladesh, employs
some 150,000 Bangladeshis and the remittance from Malaysia to this
country amounted to 67.52 million U.S. dollars in 1998-1999 fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
Labor and Manpower Minister M.A. Mannan, State Minister for
Foreign Affairs Abul Hasan Chowdhury and a 35-member business
delegation will accompany Hasina on the trip, which aims at
further cementing the political and economic ties between the two
friendly countries, the foreign minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
