<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan, U.S. Expected to Sign Free Trade Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Jordan and the United States are
expected to sign a free trade agreement by August or early
September, said Jordanian Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of
State for Economic Affairs Mohammad Halayqah on Monday.
</P>
<P>
He made the announcement after meeting with visiting U.S. Trade
Representative Charlene Barshefesky, who arrived here on Sunday for
discussions over the free trade pact.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, they agreed to pursue efforts to solve
issues regarding the free trade agreement after reviewing steps
taken so far in the field of environmental protection, labor laws,
services and customs reduction.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed that they should sign the projected free
trade agreement in August or at the beginning of September.
Halayqah said the agreement will be submitted to U.S. Congress for
ratification, possibly at the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
"We have agreed to continue discussion with the U.S. experts who
are still in Amman if some issues remain unsettled or might hold
another round of talks either through satellite conferences or
through dispatching a Jordanian delegation to Washington before the
end of August," Halayqah said.
</P>
<P>
The free trade pact is expected to create a qualitative leap in
Jordanian exports as they will be given duty free access to the
huge market in the U.S., Halayqah said.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the great economic benefits to Jordan such as
increasing and diversifying exports, improving the trade balance
and developing joint investment, the agreement will be the
strongest possible message to Jordanian and American investors,
Halayqah said.
</P>
<P>
The trade balance is largely in favor of the U.S., but there are
indicators showing an increase in Jordan's exports to the U.S. due
the Qualifying Industrial Zones in the kingdom which enjoy duty
free exports to the U.S. market under previous trade agreements,
Halayqah said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
