<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The following are the economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Saudi Arabia, Iran and Nigeria were the main trade
partners of the United Arab Emirates in June, with Saudi Arabia
being the main exporter and Nigeria the biggest importer while Iran
came first in the field of re-export.
</P>
<P>
A report issued by Abu Dhabi Customs Department said the UAE's
total trade value was 1.82 billion dirham (about 496 million U.S.
dollars) in June, a rise of 6.26 percent from that of June 1999.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Abu Dhabi Oil Refinery said the first production
line of al-Rwais Refinery condensation processing project has been
put into operation with a capacity of 100,000 barrels per day
(bpd), or 70 percent of the planned capacity.
</P>
<P>
A report released by the company said that commercial production
is expected to kick-start in the first week of August.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey's most popular Mediterranean holiday resort,
Antalya, is enjoying an increase in the number of tourist
participation in yacht tourism.
</P>
<P>
At least 8,000 foreign yachts are currently cruising Turkish
waters and this may rise to 20,000 if the Turkish and Greek tourism
ministries reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The Training College of the United Arab Emirates'
international airline Emirates has become the first institute
outside the United States to offer a U.S.-licensed program for
aircraft flight dispatch.
</P>
<P>
This was achieved through a memorandum of understanding between
Emirates and the Airline Flight Dispatch Training Centre of Texas,
which has won the approval of the American Federal Aviation
Authority.
</P>
<P>
Aircraft dispatchers are responsible for the day-to-day
operational control of airlines, covering flight planning, flight
tracking and the operational coordination of flights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
