<HEADLINE> Argentina, Chile To Carry Out Joint Naval Exercise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The navies of Argentina and
Chile will carry out between the 3 and 8 of September their fourth
joint naval drill since 1998, when both countries made a vow
towards regional integration.
</P>
<P>
According to "La Nacion" - a local newspaper-, in this
opportunity, these maneuvers code-named "Integration II", will
take place in Argentinean territorial sea in front of the shores
of Mar del Plata and Puerto Belgrano.
</P>
<P>
The drills are made up of two stages: the first one consists of
anti-submarine maneuvers, and the second one, with the
participation of the Argentinean naval aviation, consists in anti-
air, surface, cargo relaying and supply maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that during the last two years, in the south
Atlantic waters, the navies of both countries have accomplished
drills aimed at combining and jointly developing logistics
assistance in the Antarctic bases of both nations during summer
periods.
</P>
<P>
In November, the Antarctic logistics operation will start
lasting until next March. During it in an alternate fashion,
Chilean and Argentinean ships will provide support to both nation
as Antarctic bases, and will carry out naval search and rescue,
and environmental control maneuvers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
