<HEADLINE> Meeting Between Greek-Turkish Foreign Ministers Canceled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
 ATHENS, July 31 (Xinhua) -- A planned meeting between Greek
and Turkish foreign ministers, George Papandreou and Ismail Cem,
late August has been called off.
</P>
<P>
The semi-official Athens News Agency (ANA) quoted diplomatic
circles here as saying late Monday that the cancellation was
attributed to the need for better preparation for the meeting,
which is now expected to take place on the sidelines of the annual
U.N. General Assembly in New York in September.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Turkey, both NATO members, have closely gone to war
three times in the past 26 years over their territorial disputes
in the eastern Aegean Sea and the Cyprus problem, but the two
neighboring countries have since last June taken steps to improve
their strained relations by the holding of several rounds of low-
level talks and the signing of a number of bilateral cooperation
agreements.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Turkish Foreign Minister Cem said
Monday that the rapprochement between the two countries was not
superficial because they had signed nine important agreements
which included cooperation on issues of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
He said that Turkey was ready to discuss matters concerning
the Aegean Sea, within the framework of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
As for the Cyprus problem, the Turkish minister said that he
himself never regarded Cyprus as being a common problem for Greece
and Turkey and he never raised it in his talks with his Greek
counterpart.
</P>
<P>
Viewing the Cyprus issue as being an obstacle in the
development of relations between the two countries, Greece has
insisted that Greek-Turkish relations can not be normalized until
the final resolution of the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Greek Foreign Ministry spokesman Panos Beglitis
welcomed the statements made by U.N. chief Kofi Annan and U.S.
permanent representative in the U.N. Richard Halbrooke, saying
that they were very important and timely as the talks between the
two communities on Cyprus held under the auspices of the U.N. were
in progress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
