<HEADLINE> U.S. Republican Party Adopts Platform for 2000 Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHILADELPHIA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Republican Party
adopted its platform for 2000 election here Monday at the National
Convention, vowing to win back the White House for "Renewing
America's Purpose Together".
</P>
<P>
Delegates ratified the platform as one of the first orders of
business at the convention that will hand Texas Governor George W.
Bush the presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
The Republican Party's platform of policy principles retains
its hard-line positions on abortion, gay rights and sexual
education, but it eases some stands on education and immigration,
dropping calls for abolishing the Education Department and setting
a more welcoming tone for immigrants.
</P>
<P>
"To all Americans, particularly immigrants and minorities, we
send a clear message: This is the party of freedom and progress,
and it is your home," The platform says.
</P>
<P>
The platform's preamble says it is the Republican Party's
mission to "advance the founding principles of freedom and limited
government, and the dignity and worth of every individual."
</P>
<P>
Reminding Americans that Republicans are the party of Abraham
Lincoln, the platform describes the party's nominee-to-be Bush as
"a leader who brings people together" and who can meet the
challenges facing the United States.
</P>
<P>
Fighting over the legacy of today's economic development, the
platform claims that "inspired by Presidents Reagan and Bush,
Republicans hammered into place the framework for today's
prosperity and surpluses."
</P>
<P>
The platform endorses the principles of Governor Bush's
education reform and promises to make "dramatic and swift
improvement" in education so that no American is left behind.
</P>
<P>
"Under his leadership, the Republican Party commits itself to
bold reforms in education, to make every school a place of
learning and achievement for every child," it says.
</P>
<P>
"Our platform gives every American the tools to climb the
ladder of opportunity," Wisconsin Governor Tommy Thompson, the
platform chairman, said.
</P>
<P>
The four-day Republican National Convention opened here Monday
to nominate Bush and former defense secretary Dick Cheney as the
party's presidential and vice presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
"Today begins day one of the Bush-Cheney era," declared Jim
Nicholson, chairman of the Republican National Committee at the
opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
He promised that the four-day meeting would be "a different
kind of convention for a different kind of Republican." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
