<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1999 United Nations Disarmament Yearbook Released </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Monday
announced the release of the 1999 United Nations Disarmament
Yearbook, which focuses on the actions and reactions of the world
community to the entire range of disarmament issues.
</P>
<P>
The reference work also provides an overview of regional
developments as they reflect concerns at the global level, said
the U.N. officials.
</P>
<P>
The Yearbook, a publication of the U.N. Department of
Disarmament Affairs, includes information on nuclear disarmament
and nonproliferation issues, biological and chemical weapons,
conventional weapons issues and regional disarmament.
</P>
<P>
The 419-page Yearbook, published in English, also offers
information on steps that Member States have taken to confront the
dangerous proliferation of small arms and light weapons, leading
to their decision in the U.N. General Assembly to convene the
United Nations Conference on the Illicit Trade in Small Arms in
2001.
</P>
<P>
The Yearbook touches on how different approaches to nuclear
disarmament played themselves out in the Conference on Disarmament
and the Third Preparatory Committee for the 2000 Nuclear
Nonproliferation Treaty Review Conference, effectively thwarting
substantive progress in those two crucial forums during the year.
</P>
<P>
The Yearbook includes the guidelines agreed upon by all Member
States of the United Nations Disarmament Commission on the
establishment of nuclear-weapon-free zones and on conventional
arms control and disarmament, with emphasis on the consolidated of
peace.
</P>
<P>
The Yearbook is designed as a handy reference book for
diplomats, researchers and the interested public. It comprises a
succinct narrative account of the above-mentioned subjects and
others, a brief account of all explanations of vote in the First
Committee of the United Nations General Assembly, which is in
charge of disarmament affairs, an index and extensive appendices.
</P>
<P>
The appendices provide data on the status of multilateral and
regional disarmament agreements and the text of the Convention on
Transparency in Conventional Weapons Acquisitions concluded by the
Organization of American States.
</P>
<P>
They also reproduce the texts of all General Assembly
resolutions and decisions on disarmament, list their sponsors and
indicate the overall voting results and the positions of each
Member State on each resolution.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
