<DOCNO> XIE20000731.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Lends Less in Fiscal 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank committed 15.3
billion U.S. dollars in loans and credits to developing countries
in fiscal year 2000, which ended on June 30, much lower than the
29 billion dollars in fiscal year 1999, the bank announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The global economic recovery contributed strongly to the
trends in World Bank lending over the last year as successful
economic reforms in many emerging markets restored their access to
international capital markets," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the bank's lending to crisis-affected countries --
South Korea, Argentina, Indonesia, Brazil, Russia, and Thailand --
fell to below 2 billion dollars in fiscal 2000, from 13 billion
dollars in fiscal 1999.
</P>
<P>
The bank's disbursements in fiscal 2000 stood at 18.5 billion
dollars, down from 24 billion dollars in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank said the quality of lending in fiscal 2000 was
up, with the share of projects that are at risk of not achieving
their development objectives falling to an estimated 15 percent of
the total, or roughly half the rate in fiscal 1996.
</P>
<P>
Latin America and the Caribbean gained the largest share of the
World Bank's lending commitments during fiscal 2000, totaling 4.1
billion dollars in loans and credits, followed by the Europe and
Central Asia and the East Asia and Pacific regions with 3 billion
dollars each.
</P>
<P>
Sub-Saharan Africa and South Asia each accounted for just above
2 billion dollars, and the Middle East and North Africa for almost
1 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000731.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deployment of U.N. Troops in Southern Lebanon Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations said on
Monday that the deployment of the United Nations Interim Force in
Lebanon to the "blue line" continued in four different locations.
</P>
<P>
The "blue line" was drawn by the United Nations after Israel
announced the complete withdrawal of its troops from southern
Lebanon on may 24.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations said the deployment went smoothly and no
problem were encountered.
</P>
<P>
The cooperation between the United Nations Interim Force in
Lebanon and the Lebanese Army authorities was excellent throughout,
the U.N. said.
</P>
<P>
As previously agreed, the United Nations Interim Force in
Lebanon and Lebanese operational planning team would meet Monday
to commence the joint planning for the full deployment of the
United Nations peacekeepers, the U.N. added.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. peacekeepers should have been deployed in southern
Lebanon last Wednesday. The deployment did not began until Friday
due to the new Israeli violations of its border with Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations and Lebanese troops were not ready to
deploy until all Israeli violations of the border had been cleared
up. 
</P>
</TEXT>
