<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan's Trade Deficit Grows in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's trade deficit increased by
nearly 20 percent during the first four months of this year as the
growth of imports outpaced that of exports, the central bank said
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The trade deficit climbed to 707.42 million U.S. dollars during
the first four months, 83.9 million dollars or 19.9 percent higher
than the same period of 1999, the central bank said in a bulletin.
</P>
<P>
Imports in the period amounted to 1.15 billion dollars as
against 992.6 million dollars in the same period in 1999, while
exports went up to 446.6 million dollars from 416.6 million
dollars, the bulletin said.
</P>
<P>
The kingdom's exports to Arab countries, its traditional market,
amounted to 181.3 million dollars, with Saudi Arabia topping the
importers' list with 45.8 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Exports to Israel almost doubled in the period, rising to 22.4
million dollars from 11.8 million dollars in the same period in
1999, despite the fact that the Jewish state is still imposing
strict security checks on Jordanian cargo trucks.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's imports from Arab countries during the four months
amounted to 320.2 million dollars, with Iraq ranking first with
goods worth 222.5 million dollars, mostly oil and oil derivatives,
followed by Saudi Arabia with 36.4 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Imports from European Union countries amounted to 372.8 million
dollars with Germany ranking first with 107.8 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Imports from the United States, another major trade partner of
the kingdom, stood at 113.7 million dollars at the end of last
April, while the share of Asian countries as a whole amounted to
228.9 million dollars, the bulletin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
