<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Survives Critical No-Confidence Votes EDS - Updates with more details </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak's government Monday evening survived three no-confidence
votes in the Knesset (Parliament), which were critical political
tests for Barak after the collapsed Camp David summit with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The development may give Barak more breathing space for forming
a new and more solid majority in the Knesset and keeping pushing
forward Israeli-Arab peace process.
</P>
<P>
All the three no-confidence motions, submitted by the major
opposition Likud, Israeli Arab's United Arab List and Hadash party,
failed to win the law-required minimum 61 votes in the 120-member
parliament to topple the government.
</P>
<P>
All these motions are related, directly or indirectly, to the
summit talks with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, which lasted
15 days at Camp David earlier this month but finally failed to
reach any agreement on core issues, such as the fate of Jerusalem,
between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The Knesset voted 50-50, with eight abstentions, on the critical
no-confidence motion brought by Likud, which protested against the
way Barak handled the talks and the concessions Barak reportedly
made at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
The United Arab List and Hadash motions were filed over the
prime minister's "ignoring the legitimate rights of the Palestinian
people" during the talks.
</P>
<P>
Since the Knesset will begin its summer recess on August 3 and
only reconvene on October 30, Monday's session was regarded as the
last chance in the next few months for the oppositions to topple
the government through no-confidence votes.
</P>
<P>
The only exception is that the Knesset could call for a special
session to vote on no-confidence motions if 61 legislators agree to
do so, which is a hard-to-meet condition because of the recess.
</P>
<P>
Thus, Barak now have three most-needed months to maneuver for
his government's survival and for the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Barak is expected to use the time for strengthening his
government, which now is a minority government only controlling 42
seats in the Knesset.
</P>
<P>
He could form a so-called national unity government with the
Likud, or resurrect a coalition with Shas, Yisrael Ba'aliya and
National Religious Party, who resigned en masse from the government
ahead of the Camp David Talks.
</P>
<P>
He could also, although less enthusiastically, form a pro-peace
minority government with left-wing Meretz, Shinui and Israeli Arab
parties.
</P>
<P>
Most important, Barak will be free to pursue his peace agenda,
without worrying about parliamentary no-confidence votes, and
maneuver behind the scenes and try to reach an Israeli-Palestinian
peace agreement before this September.
</P>
<P>
With a peace accord in his hands, he may have enough confidence
to call for early elections to solve the parliamentary problem once
and for all.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Barak suffered a severe blow in the Knesset
when his coalition's presidential candidate Shimon Peres was
defeated by Likud's Moshe Katsav in the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
The unexpected defeat made some analysts worry that the no-
confidence votes will also produce dramatic results. Another
failure of Barak will cast more clouds over the troubled Israeli-
Palestinian peace talks after the Camp David summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000731.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Calls for Unbiased U.S. Role in Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Egypt on Monday called on the United
States to play an unbiased role in the Middle East peace process,
in response to U.S. President Bill Clinton's expressed desire to
move American embassy in Israel from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said the question of moving
the U.S. embassy in Israel to Jerusalem was an extremely thorny
issue. He urged all parties to avoid taking unilateral steps.
</P>
<P>
Jerusalem is still subject to negotiations between the
Palestinians and Israel, which should not be disturbed, Moussa told
reporters after meeting with U.S. envoy Edward Walker in Egypt's
town of Borg el-Arab, west of the Mediterranean port city of
Alexandria.
</P>
<P>
The continuation of the peace process and an unbiased U.S. role
require that no steps be taken which would negatively affect the
process, including what are known as unilateral actions, Moussa
said.
</P>
<P>
Walker, U.S. assistant secretary of state for Near Eastern
affairs, declined to comment on Clinton's declared intention.
</P>
<P>
He later held talks with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak. The
U.S. official arrived in Egypt earlier in the day to brief Egyptian
officials on the 15-day talks between Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat and Israel Prime Minister Ehud Barak in the U.S. Camp David
presidential retreat.
</P>
<P>
The 15-day talks broke down last Tuesday without producing a
peace agreement between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
In an interview broadcast on Israeli television Friday, Clinton
said he was considering moving the U.S. embassy from Tel Aviv to
Jerusalem by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Moving the embassy to Jerusalem would imply a U.S. recognition
of Israel's claim to the city as its "eternal and indivisible
capital," a position so far never accepted by the international
community.
</P>
<P>
Moussa called for sustaining efforts to secure the Palestinian
people's aspirations and legitimate rights to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians want Arab East Jerusalem, seized by Israel in
1967, as the capital of their future independent state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
