<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000731.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Says "Oil-for-Food" no Substitute for Resumption of Iraq's Normal Economic Activity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Benon V. Sevan, Executive
Director of the United Nations Office of Iraq's Program, said on
Monday that the "oil-for-food" program is no substitute for the
resumption of normal economic activity in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Sevan made the statement prior to his fourth mission to Iraq
which will take place from August 1 to 17.
</P>
<P>
It has been 10 years since the United Nations Security Council
imposed sanctions on Iraq but only three and a half years since
the first oil was shipped out of the country under the term of the
oil-for-food program, he said.
</P>
<P>
Since the first oil shipment, on December 10, 1996, around 1.9
billion barrels have been exported earning just under 29 billion U.
S. dollars, he said.
</P>
<P>
The rate of approvals of humanitarian goods has far
outstripped the pace of supplies arriving in Iraq except for food
and health where around 75 percent of supplies approved by the
sanctions committee of the Security Council have arrived, he noted.
</P>
<P>
For agriculture 44 percent of approved supplies have arrived,
for education arrivals are 25 percent, for electricity 34 percent
and for water and sanitation 23 percent,and in the oil sector
arrival are 34 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
It adds up to around 8.35 billion arrived in Iraq with around
4.2 billion of supplies and equipment in the pipeline for a total
of 12.55 billion, and then there is the 1.6 billion the Committee
has put on hold, plus more then 200 contracts for which additional
information is being sought, he said.
</P>
<P>
Even with the recent improvements in New York and the new
leadership in Iraq and improved observation methods in Iraq, the
oil-for-food program is no substitute for the resumption of normal
economic activity in Iraq, Benon stressed.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations imposed sanctions against Iraq after its
invasion of Kuwait in 1990. The sanctions cannot be lifted until
the United Nations clarifies that Iraq has destroyed all its
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations weapons inspectors have been away from Iraq
since the U.S.-led military airstrikes on the country in December
1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000731.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Establishes Permanent Forum for Indigenous Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Economic
and Social Council on Monday adopted by consensus a resolution to
establish a Permanent Forum for Indigenous Issues, an
unprecedented event in the international community.
</P>
<P>
The action was the latest step in a long process initiated in
1993, when the Vienna World Conference on Human Rights first
proposed such a forum.
</P>
<P>
The permanent Forum will break the ground. Indigenous
representatives, not only representatives of Member States, will,
for the first time, participate in a high-level forum in the
United Nations system.
</P>
<P>
Indigenous people have been seeking representation on the
international level since they first approached the League of
Nations early in the twentieth century.
</P>
<P>
The Forum will be a subsidiary organ of the Economic and
Social Council and will consist of 16 representatives. Eight
members are to be nominated by governments and elected by the
Council, and eight are to be appointed by the President of the
Council following broad consultations with indigenous
organizations and groups.
</P>
<P>
The selection process is to take into account principles of
representation and the diversity and geographical distribution of
indigenous people. Organizations of indigenous people may
participate in the Forum as observers, as may States, United
Nations bodies and organs, and intergovernmental and
nongovernmental organizations.
</P>
<P>
Historically, indigenous people have struggled to make their
concern heard by governments, the United Nations, and other
intergovernmental bodies. Their circumstances and needs went
largely unnoticed by the international community until a landmark
study was undertaken by the United Nations Subcommission on the
Protection of Minorities and Prevention of Discrimination in the
1970s.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
