<HEADLINE> French Minister Says His Remarks "Misunderstood" by Cote d'Ivoire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS,July 31(Xinhua) -- French Delegate-Minister of
Cooperation Charles Josselin said on Monday that his remarks on
Cote d'Ivore's elections have been misunderstood by the military
authorities of the country.
</P>
<P>
Josselin triggered a wave of protests form Cote d'Ivoire's
military junta and its supporters after calling on the country to
let the opposition leader, Alassane Ouattara, to run for the
president in October while advising the junta chief, General
Robert Guei, not to run.
</P>
<P>
In a statement published by the French Foreign Ministry on the
internet, Josselin said that the anti-French protests ``can only
be explained by a misunderstanding.''
</P>
<P>
``My remarks were badly understood, badly reported perhaps,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
``I wanted, in the wake of the referendum which was the first
step of the electoral process before Cote d'Ivoire can renew
democracy, to say to the Ivoirians that France considered this
first step was made with success,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that France does not want to decide the list of
presidential candidates in Cote d'Ivoire and it is up to the
Ivoirians to decide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
