<HEADLINE> Greece to Earmark More Than 2 Billion U.S. Dollars for Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The Greek government will earmark
750 billion drachmas (about 2.08 billion U.S. dollars) in direct
and indirect support funding to the country's tourism sector by
the year 2006, or 25 percent of the total national and regional
programs for competitiveness and growth.
</P>
<P>
Announcing this at a press conference Monday, Greece's
Development Minister Nikos Christodoulakis said that funding would
be secured from a Third Community Support Framework.
</P>
<P>
The biggest part of public spending for tourism, around 80
percent, would be earmarked for private investments, he said,
adding that the tourism sector would also benefit from investments
in other sectors, such as energy, transport, environment and
culture, that would affect the quality and the composition of the
country's tourist product.
</P>
<P>
Tourism is one of the most important sectors of the Greek
economy, accounting for about 20 percent of total invisible
earnings. The tourist industry provides jobs for an estimated 350.
000 people, or about 9 percent of the employed labor force in the
country.
</P>
<P>
A big increase is recorded in the number of tourists visiting
Greece this year. Over 13 million tourists are expected to visit
Greece by October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
