<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hospitalized Slovak President Returns to Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Slovak President Rudolf Schuster,
who remains yet in  an Austrian hospital, returned to work Monday
after 47 days of treatment there, said reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
Schuster said in a statement issued Monday morning that he "
signed four decrees appointing four vice-chancellors in Banska,
Bystrica, Kosice and Presov".
</P>
<P>
He added that it was not important if he could resume the
presidential power, but that he should work again to reconcile the
Slovak society.
</P>
<P>
His duty had been co-performed by Slovak Prime Minister Mikulas
Dzurinda and the parliament chairman Jozef Migas since July 3
following a joint decision by the Slovak government and parliament.
</P>
<P>
Schuster, 66, was hospitalized on June 14 for a high fever.
Austrian doctors found a puncture in his cola. The president then
had two emergency operations, which were followed by massive
abdominal infection, pneumonia and blood problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
