<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Wants to Expand Trade with Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad Monday called for greater efforts to expand the
trade ties between Malaysia and Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said he was glad that some Malaysian companies are
already operating in Bangladesh through joint-venture partnership
with their counterparts and that Malaysia was now listed by the
Bangladeshi Board of Investment as the third largest foreign
investor in Bangladesh with total investments of 1.32 billion U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
"I believe the presence of Malaysian investors reflects the
confidence that they have in Bangladesh's economy arising from the
success of the economic policies pursued by the government," he
said at a dinner hosted by him for his Bangladeshi counterpart
Sheikh Hasina at his official residence in Putrajapa near here.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said more interactions should be promoted between the
private sector of both countries.
</P>
<P>
With Malaysia's economic recovery, more Malaysian companies
would venture abroad including to Bangladesh, he said, adding "I
thus regard the continued cooperation and assistance of the
Bangladeshi government as essential to enable them to be more
involved in the socio-economic development of Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said it is important that a business-friendly
environment be created in Bangladesh to attract foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
He commended Sheikh Hasina's leadership in solving the internal
insurgency problem and in striving hard to create a peaceful and
stable environment in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said Malaysia was appreciative of the positive
contribution made by Bangladeshi workers in the development of the
Malaysian economy.
</P>
<P>
He also said that cooperation among Muslim nations is an
important dimension of Malaysia's foreign policy and that much
needs to be done to improve the lot of Muslims worldwide in this
era of globalization.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia regards Bangladesh as an important member of the group
of eight Islamic developing countries (D-8) and the Organization
of Islamic Conference (OIC) and looks forward to working closely
with Bangladesh in the interest of the Muslims world.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Hasina, in her speech, extended an open invitation to
Malaysian entrepreneurs to make Bangladesh their next foreign
destination.
</P>
<P>
She hoped Bangladesh and Malaysia would work together and help
each other in facing the challenges of globalization,
liberalization, information technology and the communication era.
</P>
<P>
She expressed her confidence that her visit to Malaysia and her
discussion with Mahathir will help further strengthen the existing
bonds of friendship, provide new insights and open up new areas of
cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Hasina and Mahathir had talks earlier Monday soon after
Hasina, accompanied by a 73-member delegation of senior officials
and businessmen, arrived here for a four-day visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
