<HEADLINE> ROK, Indian FMs Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
New Delhi, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Republic of Korea (ROK)
Foreign Minister Lee Joung-Binn Monday held here wide-ranging
discussions with his Indian counterpart External Affairs Minister
Jaswant Singh on bilateral and regional issues of mutual concern,
an Indian foreign office spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Development in the Korean peninsula figured prominently during
the talks of the two ministers, the spokesman noted.
</P>
<P>
Singh told his Korean guest that India whole-heartedly
commended the developments in the Korean peninsula, which was
indicative of great statesmanship and courage shown by the
leadership of the two countries, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Expressing ROK's hope to seek India's cooperation in the
information technology (IT) sector, Lee informed Singh that his
country would send software missions to India later this year for
discussions on joint collaboration in the IT sphere.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also discussed United Nations reforms and the
need for enlarging the UN Security Council, the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
Lee also called on Indian President K R Narayanan, Prime
Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee and met Congress President Sonia
Gandhi on Monday, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Lee extended on behalf of the ROK leadership an invitation to
Vajpayee to visit his country, he added. 
</P>
