<HEADLINE> Russia, Libya Discuss Military-Technical Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Klebanov, who is in charge of the military-industry complex,
made the statement following his talks with visiting Libyan
Secretary of Foreign Affairs Abdel Rahman Shalgham, the Interfax
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"Libya has named the priority areas of our military-technical
cooperation, including the repair and upgrading of its military
hardware, primarily regarding air-defense systems and armored
vehicles," Klebanov said.
</P>
<P>
However, "Libya did not initiate a discussion of buying new
military equipment," he said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have agreed to convene a bilateral commission on
military-technical cooperation shortly, Klebanov said.
</P>
<P>
Their talks also touched upon cooperation in the civilian
sphere, including the construction of a gas pipeline in Libya, the
deputy prime minister said, adding that Moscow will also help
Libya increase the capacity of the thermal power plant in Tripoli
and build electric power lines.
</P>
<P>
The Libyan minister, who arrived here Sunday night on a working
visit, also met with Russian President Vladimir Putin on Monday.
</P>
<P>
He handed Putin an invitation from Libyan leader Muammar
Qaddafi for the Russian president to visit Tripoli, an invitation
Putin accepted, the Kremlin said.
</P>
<P>
During the discussion of regional problems, Russia reaffirmed
its plans to ensure the complete lifting of sanctions against
Libya, said Sergei Prikhodko, Putin's deputy chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
Later Monday, Shalgham held a meeting with his Russian
counterpart, Igor Ivanov, and the two discussed ways to intensify
political dialogue and expand bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Shalgham, who last visited Moscow in 1974, expressed
satisfaction with his current Russia trip, Interfax said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
