<DOCNO> XIE20000731.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New U.N. Mission to Pave Way for Peacekeeping Operation in Horn of Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Monday unanimously decided to set up the United Nations Mission in
Ethiopia and Eritrea in anticipation of a peacekeeping operations
subject to the future Council authorization.
</P>
<P>
The decision was contained in a resolution unanimously adopted
by the 15-nation Council on Monday morning following its brief
closed-door meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Mission comprises of up to 100 military observers and the
necessary civilian support staff until January 31, 2001, the
resolution said.
</P>
<P>
Under the resolution, the new U.N. Mission is to establish and
maintain liaison with the parties concerned, to establish and put
into operation the mechanism for verifying the cessation of
hostilities between Ethiopia and Eritrea, and to prepare for the
establishment of the Military Coordination Commission provided for
in the Cessation of Hostilities Agreement.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia and Eritrea singed the June 18 cease-fire pact in
Algeria under the auspices of the Organization of African Unity (
OAU), ending fighting in a two-year border war in which tens of
thousands of soldiers died.
</P>
<P>
But enmity and mistrust remain high between the Horn of Africa
neighbors. Observers here said that skirmishes along the border
remain a possibility until the planned arrival of some 1,500 U.N.
peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Mission is mandated to assist in planning for a
future peacekeeping operation, the resolution said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the resolution also requests the parties to
facilitate the deployment of mine action experts and assets under
the United Nations Mine Action Service to further assess the mine
and unexpected ordnance problem and to provide technical
assistance to the parties to carry out emergency mine action.
</P>
<P>
The resolution stresses the importance of the rapid
demilitarization and demarcation of the common border between
Ethiopia and Eritrea in accordance with the OAU Framework
Agreement and the Cessation of Hostilities Agreement.
</P>
<P>
The resolution was adopted after another 2,500 Eritrean
refugees have left Sudan, bringing the total number of Eritreans
who have returned in the last week to 9,500, U.N. officials said.
</P>
<P>
Eritrea was an Ethiopian province until 1993, when it became
independent with Ethiopian support. Under the OAU peace plan, an
international peacekeeping force is to patrol a 25-kilometer
buffer zone pending a joint operation to define the border.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000731.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mushroom Poisoning Subsides in Central Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The outbreak of mushroom poisoning,
which killed 43 people in Voronezh this summer, is receding in
this central Russian region, the Interfax news agency reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Only six people have complained of mushroom poisoning over the
past week and only a few of those have actually been diagnosed
with poisoning, Interfax reported, quoting Mikhail Chubirko, a
local chief physician.
</P>
<P>
Russia has been beset by mushroom poisoning this summer when
some poisonous strains of the fungus changed their appearance to
resemble edible ones.
</P>
<P>
Although Voronezh is the region hardest hit by the poisoning, a
total of 28 people were killed in other regions across Russia.
Hundreds were hospitalized as a result. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000731.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New U.N. Mission to Pave Way for Peacekeeping Operation in Horn of Africa (Updated with more information) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Monday unanimously decided to set up the United Nations Mission in
Ethiopia and Eritrea in anticipation of a peacekeeping operations
subject to the future Council authorization.
</P>
