<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Republican National Convention Opens in Philadelphia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHILADELPHIA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Republicans opened their
quadrennial national convention Monday to nominate Texas Governor
George W. Bush and former defense secretary Dick Cheney as their
presidential and vice presidential candidates for this year's
election.
</P>
<P>
Attending the convention are 2,066 delegates and 2,066
alternates. A simple majority is needed to nominate the
presidential and vice presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
The convention will reach its climax Thursday when Bush accepts
the party's official nomination and delivers an acceptance speech
on the theme of "President with a purpose: A stronger leader who
can unite our country and get things done."
</P>
<P>
Bush has been campaigning in a bus tour in six Democrat-leaning
states, Arkansas, Missouri, Kentucky, Ohio, West Virginia,
Pennsylvania on his way to the convention.
</P>
<P>
Other keynote speakers in the conference include Cheney, who
was selected as Bush's running mate a few days ago, former Joint
Chiefs of Staff Chairman General Colin Powell, Arizona Senator
John McCain, Bush's defeated rival for the Republican nomination.
They will speak on the subjects of education, health care,
strength and security, as well as prosperity.
</P>
<P>
It will be the sixth Republican National Convention in
Philadelphia, America's fifth most populous city.
</P>
<P>
During the four-day conventions, Republicans will adopt a
platform with a kinder, gentler tone on issues such as immigration
and education policy, but the party retains its tough positions
against abortion, homosexuality and sex education.
</P>
<P>
Bush is leading would-be Democratic presidential candidate Al
Gore in national polls after he announced Cheney as his running
mate.
</P>
<P>
According to a CNN-Time poll released last Friday, Bush and
Cheney led Gore 52 percent to 36 percent in a four-way matchup
with the Green Party's Nalph Nader, who was at 5 percent, and
Reform Party hopeful Pat Buchanan, at 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Another CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll, released last Thursday, also
found the Republican tickets with an 11-point lead over Gore, 50
percent to 39 percent, among likely voters.
</P>
<P>
Bush said he was encouraged by polls in the presidential race
but he won't become overconfident after he saw his father lose in
1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
