<HEADLINE> Polish Lifter Wrobel Vows to Win Gold at Sydney Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Polish world record holder Agata
Wrobel vows to beat the expected challenge from world champion
Ding Meiyuan of China in a bid for the gold in the women's above-
75kg category, a Polish newspaper reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Republic newspaper said Wrobel successfully lifted 130.5 kg
in snatch and 162.5 kg in clean and jerk to register a total of
293.0 kg in Saturday's Baltic Sea Cup competition in the northern
Polish port city of Gdynia.
</P>
<P>
The paper said the three figures all surpassed the present
world records for the category but the results would not be
officially recognized by the International Weightlifting
Federation.
</P>
<P>
Wrobel is the current world record holder for both snatch (130.
0 kg) and total (290.0 kg) but China's Wang Yanmei claims the
world mark for clean and jerk in 161.0 kg.
</P>
<P>
Wrobel, who regarded Ding as her closest contender, told the
paper: "Since my situation now is not bad, I think Ding is also at
her best. I think anybody who beats the 300 kg mark at Sydney
will win the gold. This is one of the gold medals that Poland is
aiming at."
</P>
<P>
Ding won all three gold medals available in the above-75
category at World Weightlifting Championships in Athens, Greece,
in November 1999.
</P>
<P>
The paper said Wrobel claimed she did not show all her trump
cards as she gave up her third attempt in Gdynia.
</P>
<P>
Poland is sending four women and six men lifters to the Sydney
Olympic Games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
