<HEADLINE> Water Cellars Help Farmers Fight Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, July 31 (Xinhua) -- It has not rained much in
Liuhuiliang Village since spring. But Qin Changzai is not worried.
</P>
<P>
With the help of eight water cellars in front of his house, Qin
and his family were able to plant one hectare of maize, kidney
beans, and potato on time in north China's Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
"We are lucky to have the cellars," Qin said. The annual income
of Qin's four-member family is 10,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
To collect autumn rains for spring seeding by digging pits has
become a popular way in the drought-prone autonomous region to
fight drought, said Wei Hua, a local official in charge of water
conservation.
</P>
<P>
The Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region initiated an exemplary
project of rain collecting in Qingshuihe County and Jungar Banner
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Today over 40,000 households have built 88,000 water pits or
cellars and water-retention wells to irrigate some 14,300 hectares
of land. Most of the 165,000 people who lived in poverty in 1994
are now leading better lives.
</P>
<P>
The tanks have been praised by the Ministry of Water Resources.
Over 40 counties from northwest China's Gansu and Qinghai
provinces, Ningxia Hui and Xinjiang Uygur autonomous regions, and
north China's Shanxi Province have sent people to learn from Inner
Mongolia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
