<HEADLINE> Second Fishing Ban in South China Sea Ends Tomorrow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The second fishing ban in South
China Sea in 2000, from June 1 to August 1, will end tomorrow,
said Liu Guojun, a senior official with the Ministry of
Agriculture here today.
</P>
<P>
The fishing ban covered an area two times larger than the same
period last year, involving 40,000 fishing boats and nearly 500,
000 fishing labor, announced Liu at a press conference held here.
</P>
<P>
Fisherman were not greatly affected by the ban during the two
month period, Liu added.
</P>
<P>
Fishing resources in South China Sea, which contains one-fourth
of China's aquatic products, have been gradually reduced due to
overfishing in the past few years.  
</P>
