<HEADLINE> Taiwan Authorities Urged To Recognize One-China Principle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The Taiwan authorities should size
up the situation and go along with the people's will to recognize
the one-China principle and take the bright path of peaceful
reunification.
</P>
<P>
Chi Haotian, vice-chairman of the Central Military Commission (
CMC), defense minister and state councilor, made the remarks here
this evening at a reception marking the 73rd anniversary of the
founding of the Chinese People's Liberation Army (PLA).
</P>
<P>
"The PLA is firmly against any attempt to split the motherland
in whatever form, and the complete reunification of China will
certainly come at an earlier date," Chi said.
</P>
<P>
He said realize the complete reunification of the motherland
represents the trend of the times and the aspirations of the
people.
</P>
<P>
"We will stick to the basic principle of peaceful reunification
and the 'one country, two systems' policy, implement the eight-
point proposal for advancing cross-Straits relations and promote
peaceful reunification of the motherland," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are determined to stop all separatist activities that
promote Taiwan independence," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Chinese armed forces have been downsized by 500,000,
another step forward toward the goal of building a well-integrated,
highly efficient army of crack soldiers, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said remarkable achievements have been made in science and
technology for national defense. The high-tech research and
development have yielded a number of results, including the
Shenzhou space ship
</P>
<P>
He said at the turn of the century, profound changes are
continuing to take place on the international scene. To seek peace
and development and promote cooperation, the establishment of a
just and rational new international political and economic order
has become an irresistible historical trend, he said.
</P>
<P>
"China will pursue an independent foreign policy of peace,
develop friendly relations with other countries on the basis of
the Five Principles of Peaceful Co-existence, and enhance friendly
exchanges and cooperation with armed forces around the world to
pursue world peace," Chi said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
