<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peres' Defeat Is a Signal to Barak: Sharon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Shimon Peres' defeat in Israel's
presidential election on Monday sent a signal to Prime Minister
Ehud Barak that the nationalist camp is not in favor of his peace
policies, said opposition Likud party leader Ariel Sharon.
</P>
<P>
"The election was an expression of dissatisfaction over Barak's
policies and promises which he made and broke one by one...and what
happened today shows that the days of this failed government are
numbered," Sharon told reporters after the Knesset (parliament)
voting on Monday.
</P>
<P>
In a secret balloting, Likud's presidential candidate Moshe
Katsav beat One Israel's Peres by 63 votes to 57 in the second
round after falling one short of the 61 votes needed for victory in
the first round in the 120-member Knesset.
</P>
<P>
Peres' chances of victory in the secret ballot had seemed to
receive a boost early in the day from the Rabbis of the ultra-
Orthodox Shas party who allowed its Knesset members to vote as they
please.
</P>
<P>
But during the second round of voting, at least two Israeli Arab
Knesset members cast their votes to Katsav, which caused the lose
for Peres, according the Prime Minister's Office.
</P>
<P>
Looking glum, Peres, 77, said in a statement after the voting
that he has nothing to say but to congratulate Katsav for his
success.
</P>
<P>
"At this moment, the only thing I have to say is to congratulate
Moshe Katsav on his election as president...I wish him success and
all the best," Peres said.
</P>
<P>
Katsav told reporters that he will be the representative of the
Israeli people.
</P>
<P>
Katsav will be Israel's eighth president and sworn in on Tuesday
at the Knesset. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000731.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey's Central Asia Policy "Mature": Turkish FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's policy towards Central Asia
has gone through "the teething stage" and reached "maturity,"
Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem was quoted by the Turkish Daily
News as saying on Monday.
</P>
<P>
In the interview published on Monday, Cem said that "our Central
Asia policy over the past 10 years have been extremely successful.
We gave much thought to what had to be done, bearing in mind the
characteristics of the region, and we did it."
</P>
<P>
At last month's conference of Turkish ambassadors to Central
Asian countries, the foreign minister said Turkey had put "special
emphasis" on its relations with those Turkic-speaking countries
where Turkish companies were making large investments.
</P>
<P>
He paid visits to Kazakhstan and Kyrgyzstan last month amid
rising criticism within Turkey that Ankara has been neglecting this
neighboring region.
</P>
<P>
Critics said that following the collapse of the former Soviet
Union in 1991, there was an important opportunity for Turkey to
assert itself among the newly independent Turkic-speaking countries
in the region.
</P>
<P>
They argued, however, relations between Turkey and these
countries have not reached a "satisfactory" level, although it has
been nearly 10 years since these countries gained their
independence. Turkey, the center of the former Ottoman Turkish
empire whose orbit for centuries covered part of Central Asia, has
been competing for influence over the region with Russia since
1991.
</P>
<P>
Turkey hopes a 1,760-kilometer oil pipeline crossing Georgia and
linking the Azeri capital Baku with the Turkish Mediterranean port
of Ceyhan will be operating by mid-2004. The project was promoted
by the United States but opposed by Russia.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said Russia sees Turkey as acting here as an instrument
of the U.S., which is quietly wresting for control of the
traditional sphere of influence of Russia.
</P>
<P>
The minister viewed "ethnic separatism" and "radical religious
terrorism" as two major threats in Central Asia and the Caucasus,
calling for increasing cooperation on the security issues among
Turkey, countries in the region and Russia.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has been trying to enlist Russia to a "Caucasus Stability
Pact," raised early this year by former Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel, a vigorous proponent of Turkish interests in the Caucasus
and Central Asia, during his visit to neighboring Georgia. But
Russia has remained cool to the idea.
</P>
<P>
Cem told the Turkish Daily News that there was no conflict, only
peaceful but serious competition between Turkey and Russia in
Central Asia and the Caucasus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000731.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali PM Leaves for India on Official Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Prime Minister Girija
Koirala left here Monday for New Delhi, the capital of India, for
a one-week official visit at the invitation of Indian Prime
Minister Atal Vajpayee.
</P>
<P>
"My visit will enhance the atmosphere of confidence between the
two countries," Koirala told reporters at the Tribhuvan
International Airport before departure.
</P>
<P>
He expressed confidence that his visit will help further
strengthen the age-old ties of friendship between Nepal and India.
</P>
<P>
Koirala is scheduled to have official talks with his Indian
counterpart Vajpayee and discuss bilateral issues such as Kalapani
territorial disputes, the border demarcation and the duty disputes
relating to bilateral trade, among other issues.
</P>
<P>
Koirala is the first Nepali prime minister to visit India since
1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
