<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Airways Concorde Flight Forced to Land in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- A British Airways Concorde carrying
66 people made an unscheduled stop in Gander, east of Canada, on
Sunday after passengers complained of a fuel-like smell in the
cabin.
</P>
<P>
British Airways Flight 003 landed safely at airport in Gander.
Its 58 passengers and eight crew, who had been on their way from
London's Heathrow Airport to John F. Kennnedy Airport in New York,
got out unhurt.
</P>
<P>
"This was purely a precautionary measure," Honor Verrier, a
spokeswoman for British Airways, said from Toronto. "They were
very close to Gander and the pilot decided to land purely as a
precautionary measure."
</P>
<P>
British Airways engineers from New York were being flown in
late Sunday to inspect the aircraft. Meanwhile, the passengers
flew to New York early Monday on an aircraft chartered by the
airline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000731.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Condemns Assassination of Spanish Ex-Governor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 31 (Xinhua) -- France Monday condemned the
assassination of a former Spanish provincial governor by the
Basque separatist group ETA while reaffirming its support to the
Spanish government in fighting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
"France condemns the assassination of Mr. Juan Maria Jauregui,
former civil governor of the Basque province of Guipuzcoa," said
French Foreign Ministry spokesman Bernard Valero.
</P>
<P>
"France reaffirms, once more, its most severe condemnation of
terrorism under all forms and its support to the Spanish
authorities in the fight against terrorism," he added.
</P>
<P>
Jauregui, a 49-year-old Socialist politician, was shot dead
Saturday in a cafe near his hometown Legorreta in Basque in
northern Spain.
</P>
<P>
He was the ninth politician murdered by the ETA since last
December, when the Basque group ended a 14-month ceasefire with
Madrid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000731.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Ten years after it was overrun by Iraqi troops and rescued
by a U.S.-led coalition in the Persian Gulf War, Kuwait remains
reliant on the U.S. military for protection against surrounding
countries it does not trust and riven within over whether to
continue a cautious opening to Western ways,
</P>
<P>
-- French investigators said Sunday that some debris left on
the runway just before an Air France Concorde crashed outside
Paris last week appears to have come from a fuel tank, leading
them to believe that a roaring fire that enveloped the left wing
sprang from a major fuel leak and not from an engine malfunction.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Rallying to President Hugo Chavez's call for radical social
and political change, Venezuelans Sunday granted him a new six-
year term with enhanced powers to sweep away the last remnants of
the traditional political order.
</P>
<P>
-- In what would be one of the biggest strikes in a decade, 85,
000 telephone workers on the East Coast are threatening to walk
out next weekend in a struggle that, stripped to its essentials,
pits old-line labor against the New Economy.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- Nearly a third of the increase in gross domestic product in
the April-to-June period came from business spending on
information-processing gear and software, even though those
products make up just a 20th of the economy's total output.
</P>
<P>
-- A Wall Street Journal/NBC survey found the Texas governor
leads Gore 47 percent to 42 percent. Gore said he will unveil his
choice of running mate August 8. 
</P>
</TEXT>
