<HEADLINE> British, Irish PMs Discuss Northern Ireland Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 31 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
Monday met his Irish counterpart, Bertie Ahern, again to discuss
the Northern Ireland peace process.
</P>
<P>
Blair's spokesman said here that the two leaders held a 90-
minute working lunch in Downing Street and talked about the threat
posed by dissident guerrilla groups in the British province that
are opposed to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"They will discuss how the two governments can work together to
tackle dissidents," he said.
</P>
<P>
While the Irish Republican Army and other mainstream guerrilla
groups are observing cease-fires as part of the Northern Ireland
peace process, dissident gunmen and bombers have been blamed by
security sources for sporadic attacks.
</P>
<P>
About two weeks ago, before the British government held a huge
royal pageant to celebrate the 100th birthday of the Queen Mother,
British police destroyed an explosive device found in London. It
was accused that dissident Irish republican guerrillas had planted
it.
</P>
<P>
It was also revealed that the missiles, machine guns and
explosives seized in Croatia last week were believed to have been
destined for dissident Irish republican guerrillas. 
</P>
