<HEADLINE> FIVB likely to Change 2002 Women's World Championships Host </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Germany is likely to replace Brazil
as the host for the 2002 Women's Volleyball World Championship,
the International Volleyball Federation (FIVB) said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The world volleyball ruling body said in a statement that after
realizing Brazil failed to live up to the required conditions,
they decided to look for another site.
</P>
<P>
Germany has immediately filed its candidature and the
officialization should take place soon, according to the statement
released in Seville, Spain.
</P>
<P>
A record number of 61 teams have registered to compete in the
preliminaries of the championship where Cuba will defend its title.
</P>
<P>
It is also a record number of 66 teams that will be present for
the men's World Championship to be hosted by Argentina in the same
year. Italy will defend its crown.
</P>
<P>
The drawing of lots for the groups of the preliminaries for
both men's and women's world championship in 2002 will take place
at the FIVB World Congress to be held from August 2 to 4 in
Seville. 
