<HEADLINE> Beijing Passes Law to Protect Moral and Upright Citizens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Beijing expects to implement a
regulation on August 1 to reward and protect those people who are
ready to off unconditional help to their fellow man.
</P>
<P>
According to the law, the municipal government will spend 10
million yuan to establish a fund to honor these moral upright
citizens.
</P>
<P>
"They don't have to pay individual income tax, even though the
prize may exceed 10,000 yuan," said Deputy Mayor Qu Hongxiang.
</P>
<P>
The regulation also requires that medical organizations should
try to save these upright and selfless people when they are
wounded and reduce their medical fees.
</P>
<P>
If these people sacrifice their lives, the government will be
responsible to help and support their families; if they become
disabled, they may be re-employed at suitable posts or be placed
in social welfare organizations.
</P>
<P>
More upright citizens have appeared in Beijing since 1991 when
the capital started to officially commend their good deeds and
actions, added Qu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
