<DOCNO> XIE20000731.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Right-wing Candidate Elected as Israel's New President 1st lead-writethru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Right-wing presidential candidate
Moshe Katsav was elected the eighth president of the State of
Israel in a special parliamentary vote Monday morning, dealing a
severe blow to Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak as he supported
Katsav's rival Shimon Peres.
</P>
<P>
Katsav, who is from the right-wing Likud faction, won the second
round of the election with a vote of 63-57, which was sufficient
for declaring victory as the law-required vote is 61 in the 120-
member Knesset (Parliament) in the first and second rounds of the
secret ballot.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the first round, Katsav commanded a lead with 60
votes over the ruling One Israel's candidate and former prime
minister Shimon Peres, who gained 57 votes. Peres indicated before
the vote that he had guaranteed at least 60 votes in the Knesset.
</P>
<P>
The unfortunate Peres served as prime minister (1984-1986) in a
national unity government with Likud's Yitzhak Shamir, although he
lost the 1984 general election to Shamir.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, he succeeded Yitzhak Rabin's prime minister post after
Rabin had been assassinated by right-wing extremists. However, he
was defeated by Likud's Benjamin Netanyahu in the 1996 election.
</P>
<P>
The 55-year-old Katsav, who was once regarded as the underdog in
the race, will be sworn in on Tuesday for a seven-year term as the
highly ceremonial head of state.
</P>
<P>
During the election campaign, Katsav repeatedly promoted his
slogan that Israel, at this stage, needs a more central president
than Peres for the purpose of uniting the nation in light of a
widening rift between the left and the right, the secular and the
religious in the country.
</P>
<P>
Peres, who won a Nobel Peace Prize in 1994 for his efforts to
master-plan the landmark Oslo Accords between Israel and the
Palestinians, is regarded as the most dovish politician in the
Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
In this context, the election of Katsav is expected to do harm
to Barak's peace efforts to push forward the peace process with
Arab countries, some analysts predicted.
</P>
<P>
However, other analysts pointed out that the Israeli president,
who represents the country abroad and at home as the head of state,
grants pardons, receives diplomatic credentials, swears in judges
and signs laws, is a highly ceremonial post.
</P>
<P>
Katsav also repeated many times during the campaign that he will
not be too political and meddle in the government's affairs if he
is elected.
</P>
<P>
The blow dealt to Barak due to Peres's defeat, thus, might be
only at the psychological and morale levels. Barak is facing three
no-confidence votes Monday afternoon, which might be more critical
for his political survival.
</P>
<P>
The presidential inauguration ceremony will begin at 6:30 p.m.
Tuesday in the Knesset Speaker's Office, in the presence of former
President Ezer Weizman, justices of Israel's Supreme Court, members
of the Israel Defense Forces General Staff, senior members of the
diplomatic corps and other dignitaries.
</P>
<P>
Weizman, whose term to end in 2003, was forced to resign early
this month after the revelation of his financial irregularities
with a French Jewish businessman and the subsequent police
investigation.
</P>
<P>
Although the police had closed the case without indictment, the
president's involvement in such a scandal forced him to consider
early resignation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000731.0113 </DOCNO>
