<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Cabinet Approves New Constitution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's cabinet of ministers
on Monday unanimously approved the new draft constitution which
aims at politically ending the 17-year civil war between
government troops and Tamil Tiger rebels, a government statement
said.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the cabinet met and considered the draft
constitution in full and made the decision after a lengthy
discussion.
</P>
<P>
It said the cabinet will present the draft to the parliament on
August 3.
</P>
<P>
President Kumaratunga has said she was keen to push through the
draft constitution before the dissolution of the parliament on
August 24.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka has been plagued by a long-running civil war between
government troops and Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam rebels who
are fighting for a separate state for minority Tamils in the
country's north and east since 1983.
</P>
<P>
The draft constitution aims at ending the war by devolving
powers to regional councils including one administered by ethnic
Tamils.
</P>
<P>
The government of ruling People's Alliance lacks the required
two-thirds majority for the passage of the reforms and had entered
into bipartisan talks with the main opposition United National
Party (UNP) to reach consensus and obtain the required support in
the parliament.
</P>
<P>
However, the UNP, which holds the balance of power to make or
break the reforms, does not favor a debate on the reforms before
the dissolution of the parliament on the grounds that agreement
had still not been reached on several matters and that a wider
spectrum of society should be consulted.
</P>
<P>
The Buddhist clergy, smaller political parties and several
other organizations have protested that they have not been
consulted about the constitutional reforms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
