<HEADLINE> Germany to Send Smaller Athletics Team to Sydney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Germany will send a smaller track and
field team to the Sydney Olympics but hopes to win as many medals.
</P>
<P>
Frank Hensel, a director at the German Athletics Federation (
DLV), said Sunday that about 70 athletes are expected to be
nominated, compared to 91 for the Atlanta Games four years ago.
</P>
<P>
Despite few outstanding performances in the German nationals
over the weekend in Braunschweig for cool weather, DLV officials
thought that German athletes still can do as well as in Atlanta
where they won seven medals.
</P>
<P>
"That's a good team, in which almost everyone has a chance of
reaching the finals," said DLV President Helmut Digel.
</P>
<P>
So far, 67 German athletes have passed Olympic qualifying
standards set by the DLV. No more than 73 athletes are expected
to be going to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
Athletes who fail to pass the qualifying standard can still get
a place on the team if they had been injured for a long time and
if they are recommended by the DLV to the National Olympic
Committee.
</P>
<P>
Germany took 84 athletes to the Barcelona Olympics in 1992 and
the Sydney team will be the smallest since the German unification
in 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
