<DOCNO> XIE20000731.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wild Animals in China's West Regain Paradise (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, July 31 (Xinhua) -- A forestry official in west China
's Sichuan Province said here today that traces of the Giant Panda
were recently found in the province's Ruo'ergai County.
</P>
<P>
"Giant Pandas have never been found in the area before, and the
finding indicate that the living environment of the endangered
species is improving and their habitat expanding," the official
said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from forestry departments of west China's provinces
and autonomous regions show that the number of wild animals in the
region has been on rise in recent years due to the recovery of
forest resources resulting from China's efforts to regreen the
area as well as the country's enhanced measures to protect wild
animals.
</P>
<P>
In Yunnan Province, the number of the endangered golden-haired
monkeys has risen to about 600 from 200, and the Asian elephants
to some 300 from 100; in Gansu Province, the number of white-
lipped deer has increased to more than 1,000 from 300. Meanwhile,
the rampant poaching of Tibetan antelopes on the Qinghai-Tibet
Plateau has been effectively curbed.
</P>
<P>
China's west cover about 60 percent of the country's territory,
and its mountainous landscape and various types of forest
vegetation provide the major habitat for the country's wild
animals.
</P>
<P>
In Yunnan alone, the number of vertebrate animal species
exceeds 1,700, accounting for 58.2 percent of the country's total,
and the number of rare species ranks first in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000731.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wild Animals in China's West Regain Paradise (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
For years, however, wild animals in the region have found their
habitat dwindling and many species are on the verge of extinction,
mainly due to reckless logging of nature forest for timber and
farmland.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, China imposed logging ban on all natural forest along
the upper and middle reaches of the Yangtze and Yellow Rivers and
last year, launched the drive to regreen the western regions
featured by turning crops fields on mountain slopes back to forest.
Meanwhile, the construction of nature reserves also speeded up.
</P>
<P>
According to a plan recently announced by the State Forestry
Administration, China will set up 270 nature reserves, covering 65
million ha, in the western regions over the next 10 years, which
together with the current more than 400 ones will make up 13.33
percent of the country's territory.
</P>
<P>
Forestry experts say the logging ban has brought peaceful
surrounding back to the forest and also the quick recovery of
forest vegetation, which greatly improves the living environment
of wild animals. And farmland-turned forest link up isolated
animal habitat, broadening the scope of their activities.
</P>
<P>
What's more, the well preserved forest vegetation and
ecological diversity in the nature reserves provide more ideal
home for wild animals, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
