<HEADLINE> URGENT Right-wing Candidate Elected as Israel's New President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Right-wing presidential candidate
Moshe Katsav was elected as the eighth president of Israel in a
special parliamentary vote Monday morning, a severe blow to Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak as he supported Katsav's opponent Shimon
Peres.
</P>
<P>
Katsav won the second round of the election with a vote of 63-
57.
</P>
<P>
A candidate needs at least 61 votes of the 120-member Knesset in
the first and second rounds of Knesset (parliament) secret ballot.
</P>
<P>
The 55-year-old Katsav, who was once regarded as the underdog in
the race, will be sworn in on Tuesday morning for a seven-year term
as the highly ceremonial head of state. 
</P>
