<HEADLINE> Prosecution of Al-Ma'Unah Members Defers in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The 27 members of the Al-Ma'unah group who stole arms from two
military camps in Gerik in the northern state of Perak on July 2
and killed two of their four hostages will be detained under the
Internal Security Act (ISA), he said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The ISA provides for detention without trial.
</P>
<P>
The attorney-general said "I have been informed by the police
of their intended action to detain the criminals under the
Internal Security Act. Therefore, in the interest of the national
security, I have decided to defer the prosecution of these
criminals for the time being."
</P>
<P>
The 27 members have been remanded in police custody since they
surrendered to the security forces on July 6.
</P>
<P>
Their prosecution was scheduled to be held at the Magistrate's
Court in Kuala Kangsar, Perak, Tuesday when the remand order by
the court expires Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The attorney-general said his statement was to clarify the
status of the investigation pertaining to the arrest of the group
members.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his satisfaction over investigation done by the
police, saying "I am satisfied that the police have done a
thorough investigation. I, as a public prosecutor, have conducted
a detailed study of the investigation papers. I am satisfied that
there are sufficient evidence to warrant the prosecution of those
responsible under the relevant laws," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, Inspector-General of Police Norian Mai told reporters
here earlier Tuesday that the 27 members of the Al Ma'unah would
be charged in court Tuesday. 
</P>
