<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burundi Party Urges Buyoya not to Bring Country Back to Bloody War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 31 (Xinhua) -- A major Burundian party
involved in the peace talks aimed at ending the seven-year civil
war in the central African country has warned President Pierre
Buyoya that his military government is likely to plunge the
country into a bloody civil war if it refuses to sign the peace
agreement scheduled for August 28.
</P>
<P>
The independent Guardian newspaper here Monday quoted Joseph
Karumba, national chairman of the Burundian Front for National
Liberation (FROLINA), as saying on Sunday that the rejection by
the government might lead to a civil war because his movement
would not accept proposals made by Buyoya who demands he should be
given another two-year term.
</P>
<P>
"FROLINA will never allow any covert move to give Buyoya two
presidential years who has failed to lead Burundi for 13 years,"
Karumba said.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Buyoya reportedly announced in Bujumbura, Burundi,
that his government will not sign a peace deal next month unless
two conditions are met.
</P>
<P>
A cease-fire must enforced before the peace agreement is signed,
and another two-year term must be given to the existing military
government, he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, Karumba stressed that a cease-fire will only be
meaningful once the signing of the peace agreement is done on
August 28.
</P>
<P>
Burundian parties, including the Bujumbura government, involved
in the peace talks, should understand that they will not find a
durable peace by refusing to sign the peace accord, said the
FROLINA leader.
</P>
<P>
Under the draft accord mediated by former South African
President Nelson Mandela, the Tutsi minority, which has dominated
Burundi's political and economic life since its independence from
Belgium in 1962, will have to hand over power to a democratically
elected regime in three years' time.
</P>
<P>
During the last round of peace talks held in Tanzania's
northern town of Arusha this month, Mandela told 19 Burundian
parties involved in the talks that the signing of both a cease-
fire deal and the peace agreement will be done simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
Fighting in Burundi between the majority Hutus and the minority
Tutsis has claimed at least 200,000 lives, mostly civilians, since
it began in October 1993 when Tutsi paratroopers assassinated the
country's first democratically elected president Melchior Ndadaye,
a Hutu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
