<HEADLINE> Swiss Support Unit Pulls out of Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Switzerland is beginning to pull
its support unit out of Bosnia-Herzegovina after five years of
service to the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe
(OSCE), Swiss Radio International reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Their bases in Mostar and Tuzla are to be shut down on Monday.
The third base in Banja Luka will close in November, followed by
its headquarters in the Bosnian capital, Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
For four years, 45 Swiss men and women, who form an unarmed
military unit known as "the yellow berets," provided expertise and
assistance in medical care, mail service, transport and vehicle
maintenance.
</P>
<P>
Robert Barry, head of the OSCE mission in Bosnia, said that the
gap left by Switzerland's departure will be filled by commercial
companies in Bosnia and that the OSCE is inviting bids for the
jobs the Swiss have been doing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
