<DOCNO> XIE20000731.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Archaeology News: Weekly Briefs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The following is a round-up of
China's archaeology news for the past week:
</P>
<P>
-- 900-Year Old Coin Found in Northwest China
</P>
<P>
Chinese archaeologists have found a rare bronze coin dating
back to the Jin Dynasty (1115-1234) in Pengyang County in Ningxia
Hui Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The well-preserved coin, weighing 2.4 grams, is 0.9 mm thick
and 25.7 mm in diameter. There are less than ten such coins in the
world, they said, adding that the mintage of coin dates to 1130,
the year the Jin empire conquered the area.
</P>
<P>
-- 2,400-Year-Old Tombs Found in Central China
</P>
<P>
Chinese archaeologists have found a group of more than 100
ancient tombs in Jingmen City in Hubei Province.
</P>
<P>
The tombs date back to the Chu State of the Warring States
period (475-221 BC). Experts have unearthed more than 100
historical relics including bronze articles, pottery and
lacquerware from the grave site located in Shayang County.
</P>
<P>
-- Treasured Porcelain Pieces to be Auctioned
</P>
<P>
A descendant from the royal family of the Qing Dynasty (1644-
1911) recently authorized a Shanghai auction house to sell 100
treasured porcelain pieces believed to have been made in court
kilns of the Qing Dynasty and the Ming Dynasty (1368-1644).
</P>
<P>
News of the auction, which will be organized by Shanghai New
Century Auction Company on September 10, has caught the attention
of collectors and auctioneers worldwide. Experts said that only
limited number of porcelain items of the kind remain in the world.
</P>
<P>
-- China to Protect Cultural Heritage on Palm Leaves
</P>
<P>
A research center on palm leaves culture was recently set up in
Dai Autonomous Prefecture of Xishuangbanna, southwest China's
Yunnan Province.
</P>
<P>
This is the first of its kind in the country in terms of
heritage protection. There are as many as 84,000 volumes of
Buddhism Sutra on palm leaves, some Dai legends say, but most of
them are still privately kept by local people.
</P>
<P>
-- Prehistoric Museum In Shanghai
</P>
<P>
A proposed cultural museum will show the life of Shanghainese
in prehistoric times dating back some 6,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Songze Heritage Museum will display prehistoric Shanghai people
and their tombs from the Songze cultural ruins excavated in the
1950s. The ruins have more than 100 tombs containing 1,000 pieces
of jadeware, stoneware, earthenware and bone tools.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000731.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Archaeology News: Weekly Briefs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- China Relocates Two Pro-Historic Pottery Kilns
</P>
<P>
Two pottery kilns built during the Neolithic era in north
Shanxi Province were relocated recently from their original site
to a spot about 100 km away for better protection.
</P>
<P>
The kilns, in Huanqu county of the province, were part of a pro-
historic ruins which will be submerged by the on-going Xiaolangdi
reservoir on the middle reach of the Yellow River, the second
longest in China. The two kilns, unearthed in 1997, are the best
preserved ones ever found in China, experts said.
</P>
<P>
-- China Sets Up Dinosaur Museum
</P>
<P>
China has opened a dinosaur museum in Changzhou, east Jiangsu
Province.
</P>
<P>
The museum, with an investment of some 300 million yuan (about
36 million U.S. dollars), exhibits rare mineral specimen,
fossilized dinosaurs and primitive birds including a treasured
fossil of Sinosauropteryx which was found in 1996 in the northeast
province of Liaoning.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-six sets of dinosaur skeleton are shown in the museum,
equipped with advanced audio and visual facilities. The Ministry
of Land and Resources, China Geological Museum and the local
government jointly sponsored the museum.
</P>
<P>
-- 1,400-Year-Old Temple Remains Found in East China
</P>
<P>
The remains of a famous temple dating back to the Tang Dynasty
(618-907) has been discovered in Zhenjiang City in Jiangsu
Province.
</P>
<P>
The temple, named Ganlu, was built in the Beigu Hill of the
city, said an archaeologist with the Zhenjiang archaeological
research institute. The palace remains, pottery articles and
building materials unearthed from the site prove that the spot is
the ruins of the Ganlu Temple.
</P>
<P>
-- 2,200-year-old Bronze Ware Unearthed in NW China
</P>
<P>
A group of bronze ware and porcelain products dating back to
the Eastern Zhou Dynasty (770 BC - 256 BC) have been unearthed in
Zhouzhi County, northwest China's Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
Relics experts from Zhouzhi County Relics Management Station
and Xi'an City Bureau for Management of Relics and Gardens
confirmed that the 11 relics including intact bronze cooking
vessels, porcelain pots and vessels are funerary objects, which
were unearthed from two tombs of the Eastern Zhou Dynasty.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
