<HEADLINE> Nikkei Declines For Fourth Straight Day in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The benchmark Nikkei index fell for
the fourth straight trading day in Tokyo Monday, dragged down by
weakness in New York's Nasdaq composite index.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 111.08 points, or 0.70
percent, from last Friday's close to end at 15,727.49, setting
this year's lowest closing for the second straight trading day.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), which covers
all First Section issues, however, turned upward for the first
time in three trading days, rising 0.22 point or 0.02 percent to 1,
453.15.
</P>
<P>
High-priced information technology (IT) issues were dampened by
last Friday's fall in the Nasdaq, which plunged 179.23 points to 3,
663.00.
</P>
<P>
The resignation of scandal-hit Financial Reconstruction
Commission chief Kimitaka Kuze has stirred distrust over Japanese
financial policy, providing investors with another reason to sell
stocks, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section increased to 574.58 million
shares from last Friday's 570.12 million.
</P>
<P>
Akai Electric was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
The real estate, construction and air transportation sectors
marked large declines, while the brokerage, land transportation
and rubber industries were firm.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers far
outnumbered gainers 1,011 to 294, with 89 issues closing unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
