<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- After another crisis meeting with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak failed, Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy Sunday issued an
ultimatum, demanding that unless Barak takes steps to establish a
national unity government by Wednesday, he would resign.
</P>
<P>
The statement warned that if "an honest effort is not made to
establish a unity government by Wednesday of this week, I will
resign from the government and support the bill for dissolving the
Knesset."
</P>
<P>
The dissolution bill is expected to come up in the Knesset
(Parliament) plenum on Wednesday, in the final meeting of the
current Knesset session, but it will be a preliminary vote, with
three more readings necessary before it could become law.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- Despite Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak's worsening
political fortunes, he is expected to survive Monday's no-
confidence motion,the last before the Knesset's three month summer
recess.
</P>
<P>
No motion can be filed during the recess, unless 61 Knesset
members petition for such a move.
</P>
<P>
Neither the Likud nor One Israel thought that there would be 61
MKs to topple the government Monday, as Foreign Minister David Levy
did not quit the government on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- The campaign staff of Shimon Peres (One Israel) is convinced
that the Knesset will elect him Monday as Israel's next president
by a large margin.
</P>
<P>
They claim to have 60 guaranteed votes even without the ultra-
orthodox Shas and United Torah Judaism parties, while 61 votes are
needed for a first-or-second-ballot win in the 120-member Knesset
secret voting.
</P>
<P>
Peres's Opponent, Likud's candidate Moshe Katsav, maintain that
he has the solid support of between 47 and 52 MKs, so that he needs
almost all the 17 votes of Shas to win.
</P>
<P>
Although Shas spiritual leader Rabbi Ovadia Yosef still did not
announce whether he is endorsing a candidate, several Shas MKs
confirmed he has decided to grant his MKs the right to vote freely,
which will give Peres at least five more votes.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Sunday was the hottest day this summer in Israel, with no
real relief expected until Tuesday. According to the Meteorological
Service, Wednesday should see a significant fall in temperatures as
well as a decline in humidity in the coastal regions. By Thursday,
temperatures will be normal for this time of year.
</P>
<P>
A temperature of 41 degrees Centigrade was recorded in Jerusalem
Sunday, the highest in the city for July in the past 50 years. The
39 degrees recorded at Mount Cana'an, near Safed, was also the
highest there since 1956. 
</P>
</TEXT>
