<HEADLINE> Former Iranian FM Denies Candidacy in Presidential Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Former Iranian Foreign Minister Ali
Akbar Velayati has denied the report that he will vie with the
reformist President Mohammad Khatami in the 2001 presidential
election.
</P>
<P>
"I have not decided to enter the campaign of the presidential
election," he told the hard-line Resalat daily published on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Velayati, currently an advisor of international affairs to
Iranian Supreme Leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, said he prefers his
present job to any others.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Culture and Islamic Guidance Ataollah Mohajerani
said on Sunday in a press report that Velayati will probably be a
candidate from the powerful conservative camp against President
Khatami in the 8th presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Mohajerani, a close ally of President Khatami, told the
reformist daily Iran News that Iranian political factions have
already kicked off their political campaigns and Velayati's recent
visits to Syria and Lebanon are "highly suggestive."
</P>
<P>
Velayati, 55, served as foreign minister for 14 years till
President Khatami was sworn in office in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Some reformist leaders also warned that if he chose to run for
presidency, Velayati will suffer a face-losing defeat as former
Majlis (parliament) Speaker Ali Akbar Netaq Nouri did in the 1997
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Khatami won over 20 million votes, some 69 percent of the total
votes cast in the 1997 election.
</P>
<P>
Khatami last week announced his readiness to seek a second term
in office to push forward his reformist programs.
</P>
<P>
But the announcement was criticized by the conservative camp
as "premature" aiming at depriving other possible candidates of any
chance of fair competition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
