<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sixth Conference of International Organization of Paleobotany Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINHUANGDAO (Hebei), July 31 (Xinhua) -- The Sixth Conference
of International Organization of Paleobotany Opened here today in
Qinhuangdao, a summer resort in North China's Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
Some 200 phytopaleontologists from nearly 30 countries are
attending four-day event.
</P>
<P>
The experts are expected to report the latest achievements in
paleobotany and discuss research, teaching and international
cooperation on phytopaleontology in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Li Xingxue, chairman of the ongoing conference and academician
of the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS), said that paleobotany
constitutes an essential part of the study of life science and
also provides important information for coal and oil prospecting.
</P>
<P>
T. N. Taylor, member of the American Academy of Sciences,
delivered a speech titled The Role of Fungi in Early Terrestrial
Ecosystem. W. G. Chaloner from Britain gave a speech on the fossil
record of plant and environment interactions. And CAS academician
Zhang Miman made a speech on the Jehol biota.
</P>
<P>
China is the only country in the world that had Eurasian Flora,
Angara Flora, Cathayan Flora and Gondwana Flora, the four big
plantages of the Neopaleozoic. Chinese scientists have scored
significant study results thanks to this unique advantage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
