<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Book on Frontiers of Marine Science Published </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINGDAO (Shandong Province), July 31 (Xinhua) -- A book on the
frontiers of contemporary marine science was published in July in
Beijing. The book highlights 118 topics in the frontiers of marine
science.
</P>
<P>
The book covers marine-related physics, chemistry, geology,
biology and environment. And it is the product of the joint effort
of more than 100 Chinese oceanologists, with Su Jilan and Qin
Yunshan, both academicians of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, as
its chief editors.
</P>
<P>
Publication of the book will promote China's research on marine
science, which still lags behind that in developed countries, said
Su Jilan, who also chairs the UN's Intergovernmental Oceanographic
Commission. Su is now attending the on-going international forum
on oceanic science-technology and economic development in Qingdao,
a coastal city of east China's Shandong Province.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000731.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China in Bid to Control Pollution in Bohai Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINGDAO, July 31 (Xinhua) -- China will spend 60 billion yuan (
about 7.25 billion U.S. dollars) in the next 15 years to improve
the Bohai Sea's ecological environment, Deputy Director of the
State Environmental Protection Administration Wang Jirong
disclosed today.
</P>
<P>
The government has already worked out a plan for the project in
a bid to control pollution of the sea, said Wang at an
international forum on marine science and economy which ended
today in the coastal city of Qingdao, east China's Shandong
Province.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the Yellow Sea, the East China Sea and the South
China Sea, pollution in the Bohai Sea is the worst, she said.
</P>
<P>
With the completion of the plan which is due to be implemented
in three stages, the amount of nitrogen and phosphorus released
into the Bohai Sea will be cut by 46,700 tons and 15,300 tons
respectively, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
By 2015, the sea's environment will be greatly improved to
sustain social and economic development of the area.
</P>
<P>
Wang also said that over the past years, the government has
spent 25.1 billion yuan on construction of 85 sewage treatment
plants in 11 coastal provinces and cities.
</P>
<P>
These plants, with a daily handling capacity of 12.27 million
tons of waste water, have played a decisive role in reducing the
amount of pollutant discharged into the seas, she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000731.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Geneticists to Make Breakthroughs in Research (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Chinese geneticists are confident
that they will make another two breakthroughs within one year as
they quicken their pace of genome research, according to the
latest weekly of Beijing Review.
</P>
<P>
The first one is finishing their share of work on the
international Human Genome Project (HGP) by June 2001, two years
ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
The second one is to make China the first country in the world
to decode the super hybrid rice genome which is believed to ensure
China's leading position in hybrid rice research and production.
</P>
<P>
Launched in 1990 by the United States, HGP aims to map out the
sequence of all three billion nucleotide pairs, which will help
decode the structure and function of the 100,000 genes in the
human body and thus reveal a mass of information on human genetics.
</P>
<P>
Chinese geneticists got involved in the project last September,
taking on the sequencing of one percent of the human genome and
making China the sixth country to participate in HGP after the
United States, Britain, Japan, France and Germany.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last April, scientists from the Humane Genome
Center of the Chinese Academy of Science (CAS) and the National
Human Genome Center in Northern and Southern China had mapped out
the 30 million base pairs on the No.3 chromosome.
</P>
<P>
Conducted simultaneously with HGP, the super hybrid rice genome
project is of special significance to China, the largest rice
producer in the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000731.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Geneticists to Make Breakthroughs in Research (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chinese scientist Yuan Longping, the inventor of hybrid rice,
has developed numerous strains of high-yield hybrid rice over the
years. The best of them is super hybrid rice, with long-grained
non-glutinous rice as its parent.
</P>
<P>
Chinese scientists will map out the rice genome, which has 4.3
billion base pairs, one-seventh of that of the human genome.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Lihuang, director of the CAS Laboratory of Biological
Engineering, said that the project aims to discover what makes
super hybrid rice so highly productive.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the scientists will achieve this by
sequencing the super hybrid rice genome and conducting comparative
genome research.
</P>
<P>
The goal is to obtain a genome map of the rice, determine the
specific gene carried by the Chinese hybrid rice that is
responsible for its productivity, and use it to build a gene base
for hybrid rice.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhu, since the rice genome is the smallest and
most basic among those of crops, the project will also improve the
understanding of genomes of grain, corm and other corps, and will
therefore help launch genetic research on all the arable crops.
</P>
<P>
Yuan Longping, father of hybrid rice in China, said, "The super
hybrid rice genome project is very significant. It is an
effective way to raise productivity by combining crossbreeding
technology and genetic engineering."
</P>
<P>
He said that other breeding technologies, including the most
advanced genetic engineering, all end up focusing on hybridization
while the further improvement of breeding technology will rely on
progress of biological technologies.
</P>
<P>
According to Yuan, the rice genome project will help Chinese
scientists to apply molecular breeding technology to crossbreeding.
</P>
<P>
It is learned that Chinese scientists hope to start molecular
breeding research in three to five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000731.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: French Twins Marry into China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGSHUO, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Although French twins Vincenphe
and Vincent aren't identical, both wanted the same two things from
life: a wife and a home. Little did they know the answers to their
dreams were in a small Chinese town.
</P>
<P>
Vincenphe, the younger of the two by moments, visited China's
picturesque Yangshuo in the scenic spot Guilin, south China's
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region and fell in love with Chinese
culture, then with a pretty young lady who lived there.
</P>
<P>
Vincenphe used to travel a lot. But his marriage to Zhou Lizhen
and the mixed cultural atmosphere on West Street, where he started
up a restaurant, have settled him down.
</P>
<P>
The street laid with centuries-old stone and nestled between
green limestone peaks and the crystal-clear Lijiang River is now
just as well known for the many foreign tourists who stay there.
</P>
<P>
Vincenphe's enthusiastic descriptions of Chinese scenery and
culture so enchanted his twin Vincent that he left France to visit
Yangshuo in 1997, little dreaming he too would catch the love bug
in China.
</P>
<P>
"I was drinking a cup of tea in a cafe on West Street when I
first saw Qin Xiuming. She caught my eye like a flash," he
recalled.
</P>
<P>
The shy girl from the Zhuang ethnic minority was touched by
Vincent's ardor. She had just graduated from a secondary language
school, where she majored in English, and found a job in a cafe on
West Street.
</P>
<P>
"At first I doubted the sincerity of Vincent's passion, but now
there is no question of it," said Qin with a small smile.
</P>
<P>
She said when Vincent first sent her flowers, she didn't know
if she should take him seriously. Her parents warned her "a
foreigner can't be serious about love, let alone marriage. Stay
away from him." So she did.
</P>
<P>
Vincent continued to woo Qin in a broken version of their
common language -- English. Six months later they married.
</P>
<P>
They moved to France and love got its first big test. Qing, who
did not speak French, found herself idle and alone in a Paris
apartment, wondering if she had made the right choice.
</P>
<P>
A worried Vincent took his wife to his office, where he worked
as a home-appliance salesman, so she could see the demands of his
job.
</P>
<P>
"The most important element for the success of an international
marriage is that the couple should constantly try to understand
each other," he said.
</P>
<P>
Qin said she loves France but refuses to become a French
citizen. Vincent respects her choice, and has promised her they
will visit Yangshuo at least once every two years.
</P>
<P>
Vincent is even considering leaving his sales job in France and
settling in Yangshuo to help his brother manage his restaurant.
Vincenphe's Levotre Restaurant Francaise serves authentic French
cuisine and is designed to look like Qing Dynasty imperial palaces
in the Forbidden City of Beijing.
</P>
<P>
When they're all together, the Sino-French brothers and sisters-
in-law like to sit at the restaurant's outdoor tables, where they'
ve become a popular attraction on the tourist street. 
</P>
</TEXT>
