<HEADLINE> NZ Deplores Japan's Whaling Plans in N. Pacific </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 31 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Prime Minister
Helen Clark has said it is deplorable that Japan is again ignoring
world opinion and embarking on a new program of so-called
scientific whaling in the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
Clark was responding to the reports that the Japanese whaling
fleet is about to leave port to begin its plans to catch 100
whales in the North Pacific area. Japan plans to hunt 50 Byrde's
whales and 10 sperm whales as well as 40 minke whales in the North
Pacific this year.
</P>
<P>
"This year's slaughter goes beyond last year's in including not
only the previously targeted minkes, but also the Bryde's and
sperm species," the prime minister said in a weekend's press
release of the government.
</P>
<P>
"New Zealand condemns this latest Japanese proposal to
slaughter whales," she said, adding "There is no convincing
scientific reason for the Japanese to kill any whales at all."
</P>
</TEXT>
