<HEADLINE> Thailand Steps Up Efforts to Crack Down Foreign Criminals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The Thai authorities are stepping
up efforts to prevent and suppress increasing transnational crimes
and criminals which may affect the country's security and
stability, the Thai News Agency (TNA) reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Immigration Bureau was among the security organizations
that have increased efforts to gather evidences of leading foreign
criminals on blacklists and sought appropriate measures to tackle
the problems, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Suspected foreign criminals, believed to have involved in
various crimes, had reportedly operated mainly in such major
cities as Bangkok, Pattaya, Hat Yai, and Chiang Mai.
</P>
<P>
Police have arrested nearly 2,600 foreigners on various charges
over the past months, the report quoted Assistant Commissioner of
the Immigration Bureau Thepparant Rattanavanich as saying.
</P>
<P>
The charges included falsifying travel documents, visa
violations, running prostitution businesses, drug trade and
trafficking, human trafficking, and abductions for ransom, it
added.
</P>
<P>
The move coincides with Japan's call for closer cooperation
with Thai police to crack down on transnational crimes, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Ambassador to Thailand Nobutoshi Akako met Thai
National Police Chief Pornsak Durongkhaviboon recently to discuss
areas of cooperation between Thai and Japanese police forces.
</P>
<P>
The cooperation will cover joint efforts to crack down
pickpocketing gangs which have targeted not only money, but also
passports of foreign tourists to collaborate with forgery gangs in
supplying false travel documents to immigration wishing to travel
to third countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
