<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Ministers to Be Summoned to Discuss Steps on Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan President Chandrika
Kumaratunga is expected to summon her cabinet of ministers on
Monday to discuss steps to be taken in connection with the
proposed constitutional reforms aiming at politically ending the
protracted civil war between government troops and Tamil Tiger
rebels.
</P>
<P>
The Island newspaper reported Monday that Kumaratunga is keen
to push through the reforms before the dissolution of the
parliament on August 24.
</P>
<P>
The government of the ruling People's Alliance lacks the
required two-thirds majority for the passage of the reforms and
has entered into bipartisan talks with the main opposition United
National Party (UNP) to reach consensus and obtain the required
support in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
However, the UNP, which holds the balance of power to make or
break the reforms, does not favor a debate on the reforms before
the dissolution of the parliament on the grounds that agreement
had still not been reached on several matters and that a wider
spectrum of society should be consulted.
</P>
<P>
The Buddhist clergy, smaller political parties and several
other organizations have protested that they have not been
consulted about the reforms.
</P>
<P>
The government had in 1997 presented a political package for
the establishment of a Union of Regions, and had subsequently
agreed to considerably change it after discussions with the UNP.
</P>
<P>
Now with the UNP insisting that the reforms be delayed, the
president is contemplating reverting to the original package,
which has the support of the mainstream Tamil political parties.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet of ministers has been summoned mainly to decide on
what stand the government should take on the matter, which it sees
as a lasting solution to the ethnic conflict which has plagued the
country for the last 17 years and during which over 60,000 persons
have been killed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
