<DOCNO> XIE20000731.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 60 Billion Yuan For Bohai Sea Environment Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 31 (Xinhua)-- The Chinese government will set
aside 60 billion yuan (7.23 billion U.S. dollars) into the
ecological environment protection of the Bohai Sea area within the
next 15 years, today's Guangming Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Wang Jirong, deputy director of the State Environment
Protection Administration (SEPA), said that the project aims to
control the epicontinental pollution, improve and restore nearby
habitats, and better administer the coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
The project will be implemented in three five-year phases
starting from this year.
</P>
<P>
Of the total investment, 11.5 billion yuan will go tot 500
industrial pollution treatment projects, and 16.2 billion yuan
will be devoted to the construction of 166 sewage treatment
factories in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, 22.1 billion yuan will be invested in
agricultural projects and construction of shelter belts, while 8.4
billion yuan will be used to improve fishery environment and build
natural protection areas.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that the ambitious project is to reduce the
annual emission of nitrogen, phosphor and COD by 46,700 tons, 15,
300 tons and 1.611 million tons respectively.
</P>
<P>
The project will help improve the environment of the Bohai Sea
area and realize a sustained economic development in the coastal
regions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000731.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Environment News: Weekly Highlights (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Residents living near a heat-supply station in north China's
Tianjin were recently invited to discuss plans to expand the
station to make it safer.
</P>
<P>
The environmental protection agency of Tianjin, one of the most
important port industrial cities in China, has set up a system to
publicize environmental issues concerning construction projects
and solicit residents' opinions before approving such projects. "
</P>
<P>
The new system will encourage more residents to take part in
environmental issues," said a local environment official.
</P>
<P>
China Vows to Protect Bohai Sea Environment
</P>
<P>
A declaration on environmental protection in the Bohai Sea was
jointly released in Dalian on July 26 by the State Oceanic
Administration of China and Provinces of Liaoning, Shandong and
Hebei and Tianjin City adjacent to Bohai.
</P>
<P>
The document was pronounced at the 7th Program Steering
Committee of the GEF/UNDP/IMO Regional Program and Bohai Sea
Environmental Protection and Management Forum.
</P>
<P>
The declaration showed China's determination to protect Bohai
and deal with the sea contamination, according to the State
Oceanic Administration of China.
</P>
<P>
Water Pollution of Key Rivers, Lakes Under Control
</P>
<P>
Water pollution in the Huaihe, Haihe, Liaohe rivers and Taihu,
Dianchi and Chaohu lakes is under control.
</P>
<P>
Water of many reaches of the rivers and lakes has been improved,
but contamination in the rivers' main branches and some lakes is
still serious, according to sources with the State Environmental
Protection Administration (SEPA).
</P>
<P>
Pollution control in the three rivers and three lakes were
given top priority by the Chinese government from 1996 to 2000.
The chemical oxygen depletion (COD) substances of the rivers and
lakes decreased 834,000 tons, compared to 1995, a SEPA official
said.
</P>
<P>
Famous Waterfall Needs Protection
</P>
<P>
Heritage experts recently warned that if there is no
environmental protection at the Huangguoshu scenic spot, which has
18 waterfalls in China's southwest Guizhou Province, it will
disappear within 50 years.
</P>
<P>
Only 10.3 percent of the well-known tourism areas, covering 115
square kilometers, are planted with trees, less than one third of
the provincial average level of afforestation.
</P>
<P>
The experts said that water storage in the surrounding areas of
Huangguoshu has worsened. During the outgoing dry period this year,
lots of wells and springs nearby dried up. At the same time,
rubbish accumulated in the past years destroyed the natural beauty,
experts said.
</P>
</TEXT>
