<DOCNO> XIE20000731.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Environment News: Weekly Highlights (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China has decreased the release of sulfur dioxide by 1.86
million tons over the past two years as a result of its efforts to
combat acid rain and sulfur dioxide control.
</P>
<P>
A total of 98 cities in the designated acid rain and sulfur
dioxide control regions have met national standards, according to
the State Environmental Protection Administration (SEPA).
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the State Council designated 11.4 percent of China's
land, covering 175 cities in 27 provinces, autonomous regions and
municipalities as acid rain and sulfur dioxide control regions.
The sulfur dioxide releasing amount in these regions makes up 60
percent of China's total.
</P>
<P>
Glacier Discovered in North China Valley
</P>
<P>
A glacier 20 meters wide, 100 centimeters thick and extending
several kilometers in length has been discovered at the bottom of
a ravine in north China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Located in the Shitang Valley, about 70 kilometers outside the
city of Arxan, the glacier is believed to be the first detected in
the Greater Hinggan Mountains.
</P>
<P>
An 1.5-km ice-free river was also discovered just about three
kilometers away from the glacier.
</P>
<P>
An expedition team of geologists and other experts are expected
to leave for the two sites soon to explore the mysteries of the
Shitang Valley.
</P>
<P>
The glacier discovery is of great significance to research on
the geological evolution, climate and ecological environment in
the area, they said.
</P>
<P>
China Reshaping Yangtze River With Trees
</P>
<P>
Farmers at the upper reaches of the Yangtze River have turned
more than 70 percent of their low-yield farmland on slopes into
grassland or woodland over the past 11 years, greatly improving
the local ecological environment.
</P>
<P>
They have given up raising crops and switched to planting trees
on more than 600,000 hectares of farmland, according to Jiao Juren,
director of the Water and Soil Preservation Department of the
Ministry of Water Resources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
