<HEADLINE> Most Tonic Ads Found False </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The overwhelming majority of tonic
advertisements in Beijing and east China's Shandong Province are
found false, China Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
A survey by the China Consumers' Association and the China
Health Care Technology Institute found that most of the problem-
ridden ads included false or misleading information or the tonics
lacked official licences.
</P>
<P>
Seventy-three of the tonic ads surveyed from March to June in
the city and province violated the law, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The survey covered 121 tonics advertised in introductory
brochures, in the press and on TV or the radio.
</P>
<P>
"Tonic products are not drugs, but food that functions to
readjust the human body," according to a Ministry of Health
regulation.
</P>
<P>
Chinese consumers have scrambled for so-called tonics which are
described as panaceas, said Jia Yaguang, secretary-general of the
China Health Care Technology Institute.
</P>
<P>
"But their hopes have been used by some unscrupulous business
people as breaks to make easy money," Jia was quoted as saying.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
