<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Silkworm Fodder Developed in Southwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Scientists at the Southwest
China Agricultural University recently developed a kind of
silkworm fodder to replace white mulberry leaves.
</P>
<P>
The fodder was made up with bean cake, bean dregs, starch,
sugar, cellulose, vitamins and other similar nutritious
ingredients contained in mulberry leaves.
</P>
<P>
Silkworms fed on the fodder turn out whiter silk than silkworms
that eat mulberry leaves. The output and quality of the silk
turned out by the silkworm fed with the fodder are roughly the
same as that fed with mulberry leaves.
</P>
<P>
The fodder has been put into batch production in southwest
China's Sichuan Province, one of China's leading silkworm raisers.
</P>
<P>
China is a major silk producer in the world. Its silk output
makes up one eighth of the world's total.
</P>
<P>
Production of the new fodder will make it possible for China to
raise silkworm all year round, and reduce production costs, said
Wu Dayang, member of the China Sericulture Society. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000731.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Put DNA Sequence Databank on Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 31 (Xinhua) -- China has made a test run of
putting its first DNA Sequence Databank on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
The databank, a state-financed information platform, will be
officially opened on the Internet by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
The databank was developed by the Shanghai Life Science
Institute under the Chinese Academy of Sciences and the National
Human Genome Research Center of the Southern Institute of Genetics.
</P>
<P>
The databank contains some one billion subunits of gene data
including human genome data and gene maps of rice and some
livestock.
</P>
<P>
The databank is also expected to share and reprocess data from
some foreign databanks in China.  
</P>
