<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt, Jordan Discuss Ways to Support Palestinian Peace Stand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak held
talks on Monday with Jordanian King Abdullah II on ways to support
the Palestinians and their stand in peace negotiations with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Arab countries are coordinating their supportive stances for the
establishment of an independent Palestinian state which the
Palestinians have said they will declare on September 13, Egyptian
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa told reporters after the talks in
Egypt's Mediterranean port city of Alexandria.
</P>
<P>
There has been an extensive coordination of positions among Arab
states, which is based on a desire for negotiations to continue
towards the establishment of a Palestinian state on the date set by
the Palestinian leadership, Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
He added that both Egypt and Jordan would recognize such a
Palestinian state whenever it is declared, and stressed the need to
respect the relevant United Nations Security Council resolutions in
Palestinian-Israeli peace-making.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak and Abdullah, whose countries signed peace treaties with
Israel in 1979 and 1994 respectively, focused their talks on the "
very important and sensitive subject of Jerusalem," said Moussa who
attended the talks.
</P>
<P>
It was in the interests of Arab countries for the Palestinian-
Israeli peace talks to continue and succeed on the basis of the U.
N. resolutions, he added.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah arrived in Alexandria from Morocco earlier in the day
and ended the brief visit after the talks. His meeting with Mubarak
came amid intensified Egyptian contacts with Arab countries after
the failure of the Palestinian-Israeli Camp David summit last
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak had flown to Saudi Arabia and Libya for discussions on
the Mideast peace talks and met with Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Arab and Muslim countries support the Palestinian stand that
Arab East Jerusalem is part of the territories occupied by Israel
in the 1967 Mideast War and should be returned.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians want East Jerusalem as the capital of the
future Palestinian state. But Israel insists that the holy city is
its "eternal and indivisible capital," a claim not internationally
recognized. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
