present job to any others. (Iran-Presidential Elections-Denial)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Right-wing presidential candidate Moshe Katsav was
elected the eighth president of the State of Israel in a special
parliamentary vote Monday morning, dealing a severe blow to Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak as he supported Katsav's rival Shimon
Peres.
</P>
<P>
Katsav, who is from the right-wing Likud faction, won the second
round of the election with a vote of 63-57, which was sufficient
for declaring victory as the law-required vote is 61 in the 120-
member Knesset (parliament) in the first and second rounds of the
secret ballot. (Israel-Presidential Election)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and his legal
advisor said here on Monday no decision has been made to convene a
follow-up summit to the Camp David-style one which ended last week
in failure.
</P>
<P>
Barak's senior legal advisor Danny Yatom told Israel Radio that
Israel is waiting for the arrival of a new U.S. envoy who will
clarify the situation. (Israel-Summit Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak's government
Monday evening survived three no-confidence votes in the Knesset
(Parliament), which were critical political tests for Barak after
the collapsed Camp David summit with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The development may give Barak more breathing space for forming
a new and more solid majority in the Knesset and keeping pushing
forward Israeli-Arab peace process.
</P>
<P>
All the three no-confidence motions, submitted by the major
opposition Likud, Israeli Arab's United Arab List and Hadash party,
failed to win the law-required minimum 61 votes in the 120-member
parliament to topple the government. (Israel-No-confidence Votes)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon and the United Nations Interim Force in
Lebanon (UNIFIL) held meeting Monday to discuss the deployment of
Lebanese troops and the new mission of UNIFIL in south Lebanon,
Lebanon's Central News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The meeting discussed a definite date for the deployment of the
1,000-person Lebanese combined force, including 500 army and 500
police, in the villages and towns in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The combined force will be under the command of Central Ministry
and Central Security Force. (Lebanon-UN) 
