<HEADLINE> Liberia Warned to Face International Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Liberia has been warned to face
international sanctions unless it stops supporting Sierra Leone's
rebel Revolutionary United Front (RUF) fighting against the
government, reports reaching here on Monday said.
</P>
<P>
The warning came after a high-level talks in London between
British and Sierra Leone officials.
</P>
<P>
Liberia has also been warned to end its involvement in the
smuggling of diamonds from the RUF-controlled diamond areas in
Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the United Nations Security Council imposed
an embargo on Sierra Leone's diamond exports, but diamonds with
government authorization would not be affected by the embargo.
</P>
<P>
Liberia has reportedly been backing the RUF during Sierra Leone
's nine-year civil war and has benefited from the diamond-for-
armament business in the war-torn west African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000731.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sierra Leonean Government Determined to Choke Rebels of War Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leone said here
Monday that it is determined to cut off the ability of the rebels
to fuel "their atrocious war against people," and reduce the
incidence of illegal diamond exports.
</P>
<P>
The statement came as Alhaji Mohammed Deen, Sierra Leonean
minister of mineral resources, took the floor at the two-day
public hearing on illicit diamonds trade in the West African
country.
</P>
<P>
"The Government has made revision and improvements of the
current export practice," the minister said. "The Government of
Sierra Leone is determined to establish a new mining, marketing
and exporting regime for diamonds."
</P>
<P>
The proposed regime will cut off the ability of the rebels to
fuel their atrocious war against the people of Sierra Leone,
reduce the incidence of illegal diamond exports and ensure that
the people of Sierra Leone derive the fullest benefits from their
diamonds, he said.
</P>
<P>
The regime, if established, will also deter any group with
criminal or otherwise unlawful intent from operating in Sierra
Leone, and encourage the international diamond market to
contribute to peace by refusing to deal in "conflict" diamonds
from Sierra Leone, he said.
</P>
<P>
"For nine years, the people of Sierra Leone have suffered the
consequences of the illegal use of the nation's diamonds as a tool
for destruction raped, amputation, abduction, indiscriminate
killings and other atrocities against innocent civilians," he said.
</P>
<P>
"From now on, the Government is determined to use the nation's
diamonds as a tool for development, progress, wealth and
prosperity for its people," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council Sanction Committee against Sierra
Leonean rebels Monday opened a public hearing on illicit diamonds
trade in the West African country. The hearing is designed to shed
more light on how the gems are traded for arms that have fueled
the civil war in the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
