<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Starts Destroying Surplus Military Hardware in Georgia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Russia started the destruction of
surplus military hardware in Georgia on Monday in the presence of
numerous journalists, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The move was made in line with Moscow's commitments to the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE),
featured the cutting up of a T-72 tank, armored personnel carriers
and armored combat vehicles at the Russian Trans- Caucasian Army
Group's repair plant in Tbilisi.
</P>
<P>
A total of 116 pieces of equipment will be destroyed before
December 20, Interfax reported in a dispatch from Tbilisi, the
Georgian capital, quoting Lieutenant Colonel Valery Ishchenko,head
of the plant's repair service.
</P>
<P>
Also on Monday, Georgian President Eduard Shevardnadze praised
Russia for its "constructive position" in negotiations on the
withdrawal of its military bases from the Central Asian republic.
</P>
<P>
The third round of bilateral negotiations, which ended in
Moscow over the weekend, "formed a good beginning, and the
decisions that were reached are quite normal," Shevardnadze said
in a regular radio with national radio.
</P>
<P>
"If the problem of the withdrawal of Russian military bases
from the territory of Georgia is resolved with the Russian
administration painlessly, it will become a huge stimulus to take
relations between the two countries to a higher level, where there
will be more trust, more cooperation," Shevardnadze said.
</P>
<P>
During their talks in Moscow on Saturday, the two sides agreed
that August 1 Russia will start withdrawing military equipment
from its bases on Georgian territory. By December 31, no more than
153 tanks, 241 armored cars and 140 artillery systems will be left
at Russian military bases in Georgia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
