<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CanWest to Buy Major Hollinger Canadian Dailies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ottawa, July 31 (Xinhua) -- CanWest Global Communications Corp.
announced Monday that it will pay 3.5 billion Canadian dollars (2.
38 billion U.S. dollars) for the major Canadian newspapers held by
Conrad Black's Hollinger Inc.
</P>
<P>
Winnigeg-based CanWest said Monday that it will pay 2.2 billion
Canadian dollars in cash, plus 600 million Canadian dollars in
shares. Hollinger will also hold a CanWest subordinated debenture
worth 700 million Canadian dollars.
</P>
<P>
In what's billed as the largest transaction in Canadian media
industry history, CanWest, Canada's third-largest television
network, will own daily newspapers in Canada's every province
except Manitoba and New Brunswick. In total, Hollinger sold 28 of
the 58 Canadian dailies it owns, not including the National Post
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
"We are announcing a rather large convergence-content change-in
the way Canadian media will be operated into the 21st century,"
Izzy Asper, executive chairman of CanWest Global, told a news
conference Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The merger is a giant step forward in securing a bright future
for a vibrant and independent Canadian media sector," Asper, the
CanWest chairman, said in a statement. "It's also a great day for
Canadian journalists, who will have more opportunities than ever
before to tell Canadian stories to Canadians across the country."
</P>
<P>
CanWest expects that unspecified "efficiencies to be gained in
the merger" will amount to between 50 million and 150 million
Canadian dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
The arrangement, expected to close by the end of September, is
subject to approval by regulators including by the Competition
Bureau and the Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications
Commission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
