<HEADLINE> Russia May Export Electricity to Iran: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The Russian and Iranian energy
ministers met here Monday to discuss the possible export of
Russian electricity to Iran, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Russian Energy Minister Alexander Gavrin told his Iranian
counterpart, Habibollah Bitaraf, that Russia's expertise could be
utilized to build the high-voltage transmission lines Iran needs,
along with power plant construction and modernization.
</P>
<P>
The transmission lines should be built with an eye for "
possible inclusion in future to the international electricity
infrastructure," Gavrin said.
</P>
<P>
Restoration of the unified electricity system in the Trans-
Caucasus and parallel operations with Unified Energy Systems of
Russia would make it possible to export Russian electricity to
Iran, he added.
</P>
<P>
"The issue can me studied as an element of bilateral
cooperation and with attracting third countries," Gavrin said.
</P>
<P>
Bitaraf noted that Iran's electricity consumption is rising by
8-10 percent a year and that it is interested in electricity
cooperation with Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
