<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's New Parliamentarians Urged to Help Solve Economic Woes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's newly elected Members
of Parliament should contribute positively and constructively to
the economic and social problems facing the country, Zimbabwe's
Deputy Speaker of Parliament Edna Madzongwe said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Closing an induction seminar for parliamentarians, Madzongwe
said legislatures should remember that they are mandated to
influence the decision-making process towards human development
and the improvement of quality of life for Zimbabweans.
</P>
<P>
"A lot is demanded of you by the present as well as future
generations, such as ensuring good governance through well thought
out policies, laws and priorities," she said.
</P>
<P>
She urged the Members of Parliament to utilize the knowledge
they have gained to effectively discharge their duties, saying she
is looking forward to positive, constructive and courageous
exchange of knowledge, ideas and experiences in all parliamentary
debates.
</P>
<P>
The induction seminar, sponsored by the United Nations
Development Program, is aimed at equipping new parliamentarians
with skills for effective participation in debates in the
parliament, business of the House and the committee system.
</P>
<P>
A large section of parliamentarians attending the course are
from the opposition Movement for Democratic Change. 
</P>
</TEXT>
