<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Dollar Depreciated by 24 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 1 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government Tuesday
devalued its currency by 24 percent, from 38 Zimbabwean dollars to
the U.S. dollar to 50 Zimbabwean dollars to the U.S. dollar, in an
effort to promote export competitiveness and economic growth.
</P>
<P>
As part of a package of short-term economic stabilization
measures adopted by the cabinet to arrest the current economic
decline, the new decision will also help unlock foreign exchange
resources and enable the economy to begin to recover, said
Zimbabwean Finance and Economic Development Minister Simba Makoni
at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Thereafter the exchange rate will be managed within a 10
percent band in line with inflationary developments, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the government would not allow a massive free fall of
the currency because of the implications it would have on prices
of commodities on the market, stressing that a competitive rate
should be established for building up foreign currency reserves
that have dropped to unsustainable levels.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate has been maintained at 38 Zimbabwean dollars
to the U.S. dollar through an informal arrangement between the
Reserve Bank and the Bankers Association of Zimbabwe since 1998.
</P>
<P>
The arrangement was meant to minimize exchange rate volatility
and to contain speculative behavior in the foreign exchange market.
</P>
<P>
The informal arrangement, however, began to show cracks during
the second half of 1999, following continued increases in
inflation and persistent downward trend in export performance.
</P>
<P>
Makoni is expected to present to the parliament on Wednesday
the full package of short term economic stabilization measures
adopted by the cabinet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
