<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Offers Railways Operation to Private Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 1 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government will invite
bidders for the concession of operation of the Zambia Railways
Limited (ZRL) as part of the ongoing privatization program,
according to the latest issue of Privatization News magazine.
</P>
<P>
ZRL is part of the former Rhodesia railway system, with the
main line of the railway running from Victoria Falls Bridge on the
southern border with Zimbabwe to Lusaka, Kapiri Mposhi, junction
with Tanzania-Zambia Railway and then to the Copperbelt Province
with a total track length of 1,273 kilometers. All lines are
single track.
</P>
<P>
The concession of ZRL offers an opportunity for the government
to remove itself from the delivery of primarily commercial
services while retaining ownership of the key infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The Zambia Privatization Agency (ZPA) will advertize both
locally and internationally the concession of the ZRL from July
2000. Adequate time will be allowed for potential bidders to carry
out due diligence investigations before a bidders' conference.
</P>
<P>
It is envisaged that the concession transactions will be
achieved by June 2001. 
</P>
</TEXT>
