<HEADLINE> Angolan Minister on Women's Importance in African Societies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Angolan Minister of Family and
Woman Promotion Candida Celeste has stressed the great importance
of women in African societies, the official Radio Nacional de
Angola (RNA) said here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The female stratum is the fundamental element for the
construction of societies", Celeste said when addressing a
ceremony for the 38th anniversary of the establishment of the Pan-
African Women Organization (PAWO), which was held here on Monday
in commemoration of the African Woman's Day, July 31.
</P>
<P>
"Woman is with no doubt the fundamental element of societies,
besides her mission of man's companion in the battles for self-
determination of the African people," Celeste said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, she appealed to the feminine stratum to double their
efforts with a view to achieving peace in order to "fight for
development and progress of the African continent".
</P>
<P>
Niapou Traore, secretary of Information of the PAWO, said that
there exists a big gap between the legitimate ambitions of women
and their achievements, and called on the African governments to
take measures to allow women to accomplish their duties.
</P>
<P>
She also praised the institutions of the Angolan government for
the actions they realize towards gender equality and encouraged
them to stick to determination and positive efforts which are
their absolute tool of fight on the road for equality and
emancipation.
</P>
<P>
The Pan-African Women Organization was founded on July 31, 1962
in Tanzania by a group of African women from some independent
countries and representatives from liberation organizations.
</P>
</TEXT>
