<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Trade Unions to Hold One-Day Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Acting President of the Zimbabwe
Congress of Trade Unions (ZCTU) Isaac Matongo said Tuesday that
the proposed three-day strike will now take place on Wednesday
only.
</P>
<P>
The stayaway scheduled for Wednesday to Friday was intended to
force the government to restore law and order in the country.
</P>
<P>
Matongo told the Zimbabwe News Agency that ZCTU had decided
that the stayaway be held for a day only as a warning to the
government.
</P>
<P>
"It is just a firing shot to the government to reconsider
restoration of law and order in the country," said Matongo, adding:
"If the government does not do that we will go back to the drawing
board for more days."
</P>
<P>
He urged the workers to stay at home, saying it would distance
itself from those who would demonstrate.
</P>
<P>
He said action by ZCTU was not politically motivated to support
white commercial farmers, who are allegedly harassed by war
veterans occupying farms.
</P>
<P>
Police spokesman Wayne Bvudzijena said Tuesday that the police
would maintain a high level of alertness and visibility to protect
law abiding citizens from undue harassment by those orchestrating
the stayaway.
</P>
<P>
He said members of the public were free to go about their usual
day-to-day activities and must immediately report to the nearest
police station should they be forced to join in any activity they
did not want.
</P>
<P>
President of the opposition Movement for Democratic Change
Morgan Tsvangirai endorsed Wednesday's strike and urged all
Zimbabweans to support the move if they are to "restore peace and
order in this country".
</P>
<P>
He said the rule of law must be restored if the country was to
make any meaningful progress. 
</P>
