<HEADLINE> Zambia to Continue Protecting Elephants: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 1 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government will
continue its efforts to protect elephants in the country until
their population returns to 280,000, Zambian Tourism Minister
Cecil Holmes told the parliament Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The government has no plans to crop elephants in the country
because the population of the jumbos is already small; instead it
is putting in place more measures to protect the elephants from
poaching, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He said at present the elephant population in the country
stands at about 35,000, a drastic reduction from the elephant
population in the 1960s and 1970s when the population was about
280,000.
</P>
<P>
According to Zambian Vice President Christone Tembo, the
elephant population has declined as a result of rampant poaching
in the country. 
