<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Open Nationwide Tree-planting Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian President Olusegun
Obasanjo will flag off a national tree-planting campaign on August
6, Nigerian press reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Environment Alhaji Adamu who disclosed this in
Abuja on Monday, reaffirmed the government's commitment to
checking desert encroachment, soil erosion and land degradation
through its forestation program.
</P>
<P>
He said the theme of the campaign would be "Poverty,
Environment and Forests" in recognition of the roles forests play
in poverty alleviation among the rural populace and in
environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
The campaign would be managed by governors at state and local
council levels by their chairmen, he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister explained that states had been urged to designate
sites of not less than 50 hectares in each local council area
where yearly continuous tree-planting exercise would be carried
out until the site was exhausted.
</P>
<P>
Above 70 percent of Nigeria's territory was covered by forests
in the 1960s. But with the booming of oil and manufacturing
industry, many parts of the country's ecological systems have been
damaged and the forestation rate degraded to some 30 percent now.
</P>
