<P>
LUANDA, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Cape Verde's main opposition party
has showed strong opposition to Prime Minister Carlos Veiga's
decision to step down to prepare campaign for the country's
presidency in 2001, the Portuguese News Agency Lusa reported here
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the reports, the African Party for the
Independence of Cape Verde (PAICV) Monday said that it would seek
a meeting with the prime minister to express its "perplexity and
indignation over the prime minister's decision".
</P>
<P>
Veiga announced last Saturday that he had the intention to run
for president in 2001 and would not continue to act as the country
's prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Antonio Gualberto do Rosario, who replaced Veiga as
leader of the ruling Movement for Democracy (MPD) on July 1, was
nominated as acting prime minister of the west African island
country.
</P>
<P>
PAICV's leader Jose Maria Neves said the decision made by Veiga
showed "profound disrespect for the rules of the democratic game",
adding that Veiga should continue as prime minister as he has only
stated his "intention to run".
</P>
<P>
Neves said that under Cape Verde's law, a citizen is only a
candidate for president when the respective candidacy application
has been publicly accepted by the country's Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
PAICV was Cape Verde's ruling party in 1975 to 1991. The
country has since then been governed by the MPD. 
</P>
