<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Delegates from 20 African
countries gathered here Monday, attending a two-week course aimed
at training African trade negotiators for the next round of the
World Trade Organization (WTO) talks, South African Business Day
newspaper reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The course, which is funded by the Australian Agency for
International Development, was announced by Australian Prime
Minister John Howard last year at the Commonwealth Heads of
Government Meeting in Durban, South Africa.
</P>
<P>
"As both South Africa and Australia know, winning concessions
from such tough negotiators as the European Union requires a
highly professional trade negotiation team with an in-depth
knowledge of many complex issues," Australia's High Commissioner
to South Africa David Connolly said at the opening ceremony of the
course.
</P>
<P>
He said that as the last WTO round in Seattle showed, there was
growing disquiet among some members of the international community
about where international trade liberalization was taking them.
</P>
<P>
"Questions of equity and the share of the developing world in
the opportunities offered by globalization are increasingly being
asked," said Connolly, adding: "As far as developing countries are
concerned (about the answers), it depends on how successfully they
argue their respective cases during negotiations."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that developing countries need representatives
capable of effectively delivering their message to better secure
their key trade interests in negotiations. 
