<HEADLINE> Nigerian Central Bank Takes Measures to Protect Local Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 1 (Xinhua) -- To restrict illegal purchase of
foreign currencies and protect the value of local currency naira,
Nigeria's Central Bank has ordered the country's banks to reject
collecting import duty of transactions without form "M".
</P>
<P>
Form "M" is a document required by importers to provide
information on the nature of goods being imported and guarantee
that the importer has the necessary funds to back up the foreign
currency value to pay for the goods.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian press Tuesday quoted the Central Bank of Nigeria as
saying that the move was in response to the persisting high demand
for foreign currencies at the Inter-bank Foreign Exchange Market (
IFEM) by banks.
</P>
<P>
The move was also meant to make it easier for the apex bank to
detect illegal foreign exchange purchases, especially those
without the prescribed imported items, according to local
newspaper reports.
</P>
<P>
The banking industry has been inundated recently with reports
of illegal foreign exchange dealings by banks through their
clients which caused the persistent high demands in IFEM that have
continued to depreciate the value of naira against major foreign
currencies.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's currency naira has seen a quick depreciation from a
former rate of 100 naira to one U.S. dollar to that of about 115
naira to one dollar within last month alone, causing fears that
the country's fragile economy basing on imports may be damaged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
