<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Double Assistance May End Africa Aid Independence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 1 (Xinhua) -- African countries can end
their dependence on international aid next decade if the current
amount of assistance is doubled to give a push to their economies,
a U.N. report has said.
</P>
<P>
The report, released recently by the United Nations Conference
on Trade and Development, said a study on capital flows and growth
in Africa suggests that the only feasible way to end aid
dependence is to launch a massive aid program that will allow
domestic savings and external private flows to gradually replace
official flows, the independent Guardian newspaper here reported
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
An increase in official flows to 20 billion U.S. dollars could
trigger a virtuous circle of rising national savings and
investment and faster growth in sub-Saharan Africa, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, sustainable and rapid growth should attract
external private capital flow. Donor fatigue would thus give way
to investor enthusiasm and private capital would gradually replace
official flows, it explained.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. economists draw their conclusion on lessons from
experiences in Asia and Latin America. They assume that a 6-
percent growth target, with domestic investment rising at 22
percent, would increase savings and capital consumption by some 30
percent at the end of the next ten years.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the net total capital inflows to sub-
Saharan Africa, excluding Nigeria, have declined over the past
three decades. Private flows today represent less than 2 percent
of GDP for the region, which is half the average in other
developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000731.0343 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
