<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Army to Spearhead Land Resettlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 1 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe National Army has now
taken center stage in the land resettlement program, having been
brought in to help with the logistics of the massive movement of
people to the acquired farms before the onset of the rains in
November, The Herald reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
About 500,000 families are ready to be resettled on the land
that has been acquired by the government under the fast-track
resettlement program, which is designed to bring stability to the
agriculture sector.
</P>
<P>
The army will provide logistics and set up communication
centers countrywide as the government speeds up the land
redistribution program.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Inter-Ministerial Committee on Land Ignatius
Chombo, who is also Minister of Local Government, Public Works and
National Housing, said in an interview on Monday that the army
would take care of the relocation of thousands of land-starved
people by providing transport.
</P>
<P>
"The involvement of the army is to do with the sharing of
transport and personnel. It has the vehicles needed to move
people from one point to the other. It will also establish a
communication center to ensure decisions are made fast and
implemented," Chombo said.
</P>
<P>
The government has to date acquired 211 farms, measuring 560,
000 hectares, on which more than 37,000 families will be resettled
on plots of at least 15 hectares.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Lands, Agriculture and Resettlement Joseph Made
told The Herald newspaper that it was no secret that white
commercial farmers use only 30 percent of the arable farming land
they have.
</P>
<P>
"This means two-thirds of the 12 million hectares they have
should find its way to the majority of the people," Made said.
</P>
</TEXT>
