<HEADLINE> Mexico Heads UNESCO's List of Protected Zones in L. America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Mexico is the Latin American
country with the highest number of humankind heritage protected
zones declared by the United Nations Education and Science
Organization, said on Monday an expert.
</P>
<P>
Javier Villalobos, Vice President of the International Council
of Monuments and Sites in Mexico, said that of UNESCO's 600
protected sites for its historical value throughout the world, 25
are in Mexican territory.
</P>
<P>
The country has 27,000 archaeological sites, most of them in
the south, so many Mexican sites and cities are being studied for
its consideration within UNESCO's list, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Mexican cities declared mankind cultural heritage are
Mexico City, Oaxaca, Puebla, Guanajuato, Morelia, Zacatecas,
Queretaro and Campeche, said the expert.
</P>
<P>
Many archaeological zones are in this list: Teotihuacan (Mexico
State), Palenque (Chiapas), Tajin (Veracruz), Monte Alban (Oaxaca),
Uxmal (Quintana Roo) and Xochicalco (Morelos).
</P>
<P>
Also in the list are the rupestrian paintings in the San
Francisco mountain range (Baja California), the convents of the
XVI century (in Michoacan and Puebla), the Cabanas hospice (
Jalisco), Xochimilco (Mexico City) and Tlacotalpan (Veracruz).
</P>
<P>
Among the 23 Latin American cities in UNESCO's list are eight
Mexican cities, five Brazilian cities, two Peruvian cities, two
Bolivian cities and one city to Colombia, Ecuador, Guatemala, Cuba,
Venezuela and Uruguay, each.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
