<HEADLINE> Mexico Issues 5.45 Billion U.S.Dollars in Bonds Abroad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Resources were destined to re-finance obligations during the
first months of President-elect Vicente Fox's government, said
SHCP on Monday in a press release.
</P>
<P>
Fox, of the Alliance for the Change headed by the National
Action Party (PAN), winner in July 2 elections, will take office
on December 1 as the first president coming from the opposition in
71 years.
</P>
<P>
According to SHCP, the bonds improved Mexico's foreign debt
profile and reduced reimbursements in more than 3 billion U.S.
dollars between 2000 and 2003.
</P>
<P>
The last five government changes in Mexico have been
characterized by sudden economic crisis followed by capital leaks
and devaluations.
</P>
<P>
The current president, Ernesto Zedillo ruled out any new crisis
with the change of government due to solid finances in the country.
</P>
<P>
SHCP said that the successful bond issue abroad shows there is
confidence from the international community in the country's
finances.
</P>
<P>
Mexico's foreign debt amounts to some 159 billion dollars and
is Latin America's second one after Brazil's 232 billion dollars.
</P>
