<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Rebound From Selloff Last Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks rebounded
Monday as investors returned to the market for bargain-hunting
after a big selloff last week.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 10.81 at 10,521.98.
The blue chip index fell 2 percent last week.
</P>
<P>
The technology heavy Nasdaq composite index rose 103.99 at 3,
766.99, recovering from a big loss of 431.45 points or 10.5
percent last week.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor'
s 500 index rose 10.94 at 1,430.83.
</P>
<P>
Stocks rose as investors moved in the market to search for
stocks in lower prices following last week's decline. Hewlett
Packard and American Express led the Dow's advance and chip makers
and Internet and computer companies, which include Oracle and
Yahoo!, drove the Nasdaq index higher.
</P>
<P>
But traders remained nervous about higher interest rates when
they went hunting bargains.
</P>
<P>
The market plunged Friday after a government report said the U.
S. gross domestic product rose at an annual rate of 5.2 percent in
the second quarter. The stronger-than-expected growth renewed
fears of higher rates because it runs against a majority belief
that the U.S. economy is slowing after six hikes in rates in the
past 13 months.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE rose 1.47 at 640.63 and the American Stock Exchange
index rose 3.64 at 906.44. The Russell 2000 index of smaller
companies rose 10.42 at 500.64.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by an 8-to-5 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,723 up, 1,172 down and 505
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume declined to 925.23 million shares from 974.62
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
