<HEADLINE> British Army Dismantles Security Post in N.Irleand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Britain began to dismantle an army
observation post in an area of Northern Ireland, police said on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The fortified observation tower dominates the center of the
town of Crossmaglen, in South Armagh.
</P>
<P>
It was built in 1976 in the strongly republican area and was
being taken down in line with Britain's program of
demilitarization of Northern Ireland as part of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Police said in a statement that after talks with the army,
Northern Ireland's chief constable, Sir Ronnie Flanagan, "has
today announced that work will immediately commence to demolish
the observation tower situated in the square in Crossmaglen".
</P>
<P>
The South Armagh countryside bordering the Irish Republic was
dubbed "bandit country" during 30 years of guerrilla conflict over
British rule of Northern Ireland because of the high level of
attacks on British forces.
</P>
<P>
The British government hoped to take "substantial measures"to
normalize security arrangements by June 2001, the new deadline by
which both London and Dublin aim to secure full implementation of
the Good Friday Agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
