<HEADLINE> Bolivia Demands Open Markets to Complete Cocaine Eradication </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Bolivia will make a call to
the United States and the European Union to open their markets to
Bolivian products as a way to compensate its efforts made to
eradicate coca production.
</P>
<P>
Jose Luis Lupo, minister of economic development, said at a
press conference in the capital city of La Paz Monday that Bolivia
must substitute an economy based on the growth of coca for another
one based on alternate development, exports and foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
He said that when the "coca-zero" goal by the year 2002, there
won't be a further need for foreign assistance. There will only be
a need for open markets in the United States and Europe as a
compensation for the economic loss of tons of drugs prevented from
going out of Bolivian territory.
</P>
<P>
Lupo said that there is not a formal draft of this plan yet.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the coca leaf eradication program, along
with other steps considered in the Customs Law, has had a "
devastating" effect on the Bolivian commercial sector, which in
some regions has suffered a fall of 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
Bolivia has cleared during the last three years over 30,000
hectares of coca leaf crops. Nonetheless, there are still other 5,
000 hectares more to clear.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Guillermo Fortun said that Bolivia will have
eradicated all of the illegal crops by the end of 2001, that is, a
year ahead of the schedule set by the Dignity Plan, elaborated to
wipe out illegal crops.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting with foreign journalists, Fortun warned that
without an economic alternative, peasants will go back to coca
leaf production.
</P>
<P>
He added that the eradication should be carried out through a "
nation-wide state policy" and a "permanent labor" to be observed
by future governments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
