<HEADLINE> HSBC Profits Boosted By A Fall In Bad Debts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 31 (Xinhua) -- HSBC Holdings, the global banking
giant, has reported a 28 percent increase in profits at its half-
year stage, partly on the back of a big decrease in bad debts so
far this year.
</P>
<P>
In the six months to June 30 the group has made pre-tax profits
of 3.32 billion pounds compared with 2.6 billion in the same
period last year, HSBC announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
HSBC also said it had agreed the sale of its brokerage,
Charterhouse Securities, to ING Barings, a division of Dutch
bankers ING Group, for 127.4 billion pounds.
</P>
<P>
HSBC Chairman John Bond said, "HSBC's results for the first
half of 2000 were encouraging. In the UK, we saw strong
competition from traditional providers of financial services and a
fierce challenge from new entrants."
</P>
<P>
"We view the remainder of 2000 with optimism although
unexpected shocks to the financial system can never be ruled out,"
he added. 
