<DOCNO> XIE20000731.0364 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuela Opposition Candidate Vows To Continue Fighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
During a press conference, Arias recognized the victory of his
opponent, but he doesn't think of himself as defeated, on the
contrary, saying he has a great responsibility before more than
two million Venezuelans who trusted his political proposals.
</P>
<P>
Arias said that he will always be watching over every situation
to come in Venezuela's political life, and will fight for freedom
and democracy.
</P>
<P>
Arias was, along with president Hugo Chavez, one of the members
of the military to participate in Venezuela's 1992 coup d'etat
attempt. He also participated with Chavez in its revolutionary
proposal, but ceased to work with him due to disagreements.
</P>
<P>
With 84 percent of the votes counted, the National Electoral
Council gave 59 percent to Chavez and 38 percent to his main
challenger, former Zulia Gov. Francisco Arias Cardenas. Turnout
among the 12 million eligible voters was higher than expected, at
56 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000731.0365 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Approves 12.5 Million U.S. Dollars Disbursement to Rwanda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 1 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund (
IMF) has completed the first review of Rwanda's second annual
arrangement under the Poverty Reduction and Growth Facility and
approved a 12.5 million U.S. dollars disbursement under this
program, Rwanda News Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The news agency quoted a press release from the IMF as saying
that the newly approved amount brings the total disbursements
under the three-year program to about 56.3 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
"The (IMF) directors commended the Rwandan authorities for their
success in maintaining macro-economic stability with solid growth
and low inflation," said Shigemitsu Sugisaki, Deputy Managing
Director and Acting Chairman of the IMF, in the press release
after the Executive Board's discussions on Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
"They welcomed the strong measures the authorities have taken
to address the difficulties in the fiscal area faced in 1999, and
to accelerate structural reforms where progress has been slower
than envisaged," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said this has provided a basis for the completion of the
review and a consolidation of Rwanda's good track record of policy
performance.
</P>
<P>
"The authorities were encouraged to vigorously implement the
recently initiated measures to improve revenue collection,
including the strengthening of tax and customs administration and
envisaged introduction of the Value Added Tax in early 2001," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Shigemitsu highlighted that the domestic resource mobilization
is essential for ensuring the sustainability of Rwanda's social
and other anti-poverty spending programs in the medium term while
allowing a decline in its heavy dependence on external aid over
time.
</P>
<P>
IMF officials noted with satisfaction that the Rwandan
authorities, when faced with revenue shortfalls, has protected the
envisaged increase in recurrent social spending and has been able
to reduce expenditure in non-priority areas.
</P>
<P>
They stressed the importance of putting in place a medium-term
expenditure framework-linking budget lines more directly to
envisaged outcomes as well as adequate expenditure tracking
systems and beneficiary surveys to monitor the impact of spending.
</P>
<P>
The IMF directors encouraged the Rwandan authorities to further
enhance the level and efficiency of social and other anti-poverty
spending and to identify such priority spending items in the
budget, starting with mid-2000.
</P>
<P>
They also encouraged the Rwandan authorities to continue their
efforts to enhance the transparency of the budget preparation and
execution process, systematically produce public accounts and
submit government financial operations to audits by the Auditor
General.
</P>
<P>
Rwandan Minister of Finance Donald Kaberuka hailed the support
by the IMF which he said will balance the deteriorating terms of
trade and high exchange rates of the Rwandan currency against
foreign currencies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
